{"title_page": "Carlos Al\u00f3s-Ferrer", "text_new": "{{Infobox economist|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1970|11|22}}|birth_place=[[Moncofa]], [[Spain]]|name=Carlos Al\u00f3s-Ferrer|nationality=Spain|institution=[[University of Zurich]]|field=[[Neuroeconomics]], [[decision theory]], [[game theory]]|image=CAF.jpg}}'''Carlos Al\u00f3s-Ferrer''' (born November 22, 1970, in [[Moncofa]], Spain) is a professor of decision and neuroeconomic theory at the [[University of Zurich]] and is currently the editor in chief of the ''[[Journal of Economic Psychology]]''.\n\nHe holds a M.Sc. in mathematics from the [[University of Valencia]] (Spain, 1992) and a Ph.D. in economics from the [[University of Alicante]] (Spain, 1998).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.econ.uzh.ch/dam/jcr:e610367a-a901-4de6-9f37-4a9d8e063ed2/CV-Alos-Ferrer.pdf|title=CV Al\u00f3s-Ferrer|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> He has been assistant professor at the [[University of Vienna]] (Austria, 1997\u20132002), associate professor at the [[University of Salamanca]] (Spain, 2002\u20132004), and associate professor at the University of Vienna (2004\u20132005). He became a full professor of microeconomics at the [[University of Konstanz]] (Germany, 2005) and later moved to the [[University of Cologne]] (Germany, 2012).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.econ.uzh.ch/en/people/faculty/alos-ferrer.html|title=Short Biography on University of Zurich website|last=|first=|date=|website=www.econ.uzh.ch/en/people/faculty/alos-ferrer.html|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-07-11}}</ref> In 2018, he joined the [[University of Zurich]] as professor of decision and neuroeconomic theory (endowed by the NOMIS foundation).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.econ.uzh.ch/en/newsandmedia/media/2018.html|title=Announcements of the Department of Economics, University of Zurich|last=|first=|date=|website=News and Media 2018|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-07-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nomisfoundation.ch/news/carlos-alos-ferrer-named-nomis-professor-for-decision-and-neuroeconomic-theory-at-the-university-of-zurich/|title=Announcement NOMIS foundation|last=|first=|date=|website=The NOMIS Foundation|language=en-US|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-07-12}}</ref>\n\nAl\u00f3s-Ferrer has worked extensively in [[game theory]], [[bounded rationality]], [[Social choice theory|social choice]], and  [[behavioral economics]]. From 2012 to 2018, he was speaker of the interdisciplinary research unit \"Psychoeconomics,\" which used methods from psychology, economics, and neuroscience to study human decision making, and was funded by the [[Deutsche Forschungsgemeinschaft|German Research Foundation]] (DFG).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dfg.de/en/service/press/press_releases/2012/press_release_no_18/index.html|title=DFG Announcement of Funded Projects|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-07-09}}</ref>  Since January 2019, he is the editor in chief of the ''[[Journal of Economic Psychology]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iarep.org/images/2019_IAREP_Spring_newsletter_20190606.pdf|title=Newsletter IAREP|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-07-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.journals.elsevier.com/journal-of-economic-psychology|title=Journal of Economic Psychology website|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-07-09}}</ref> His research interests are [[neuroeconomics]], [[decision theory]], [[game theory]], evolution and learning in games and markets.\n\n== Selected publications ==\n\n* Al\u00f3s-Ferrer, Carlos (2018). ''A Review Essay on Social Neuroscience: Can Research on the Social Brain and Economics Inform Each Other?'', '''Journal of Economic Literature''', 56 (1), pp.&nbsp;234\u2013264.\n* Al\u00f3s-Ferrer, Carlos and Klaus Ritzberger (2016). ''The Theory of Extensive Form Games''. Springer-Verlag Berlin Heidelberg. {{ISBN|978-3-662-49942-9}}.\n* Achtziger, Anja and Carlos Al\u00f3s-Ferrer (2014). ''Fast or Rational? A Response-Times Study of Bayesian Updating'', '''Management Science''', 60 (4), pp.&nbsp;923\u2013938.\n* Achtziger, Anja, Carlos Al\u00f3s-Ferrer, Sabine H\u00fcgelsch\u00e4fer, and Marco Steinhauser (2014). ''The Neural Basis of Belief Updating and Rational Decision Making'', '''Social Cognitive and Affective Neuroscience''', 9 (1), pp.&nbsp;55\u201362.\n* Al\u00f3s-Ferrer, Carlos and Nick Netzer (2010). ''The Logit-Response Dynamics'', '''Games and Economic Behavior''', 68 (2), pp.&nbsp;413\u2013427.\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [https://www.econ.uzh.ch/en/people/faculty/alos-ferrer.html University of Zurich, personal webpage].\n\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:University of Zurich faculty]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox economist|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1970|11|22}}|birth_place=[[Moncofa]], [[Spain]]|name=Carlos Al\u00f3s-Ferrer|nationality=Spain|institution=[[University of Zurich]]|field=[[Neuroeconomics]], [[decision theory]], [[game theory]]|image=CAF.jpg}}'''Carlos Al\u00f3s-Ferrer''' (born November 22, 1970, in [[Moncofa]], Spain) is a professor of decision and neuroeconomic theory at the [[University of Zurich]] and is currently the editor in chief of the ''[[Journal of Economic Psychology]]''.\n\nHe holds a M.Sc. in mathematics from the [[University of Valencia]] (Spain, 1992) and a Ph.D. in economics from the [[University of Alicante]] (Spain, 1998).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.econ.uzh.ch/dam/jcr:9f23db22-8a7e-4003-ab1f-656a05516a33/CV-Alos-Ferrer.pdf|title=CV Al\u00f3s-Ferrer|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> He has been assistant professor at the [[University of Vienna]] (Austria, 1997\u20132002), associate professor at the [[University of Salamanca]] (Spain, 2002\u20132004), and associate professor at the University of Vienna (2004\u20132005). He became a full professor of microeconomics at the [[University of Konstanz]] (Germany, 2005) and later moved to the [[University of Cologne]] (Germany, 2012).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.econ.uzh.ch/en/people/faculty/alos-ferrer.html|title=Short Biography on University of Zurich website|last=|first=|date=|website=www.econ.uzh.ch/en/people/faculty/alos-ferrer.html|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-07-11}}</ref> In 2018, he joined the [[University of Zurich]] as professor of decision and neuroeconomic theory (endowed by the NOMIS foundation).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.econ.uzh.ch/en/newsandmedia/media/2018.html|title=Announcements of the Department of Economics, University of Zurich|last=|first=|date=|website=News and Media 2018|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-07-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nomisfoundation.ch/news/carlos-alos-ferrer-named-nomis-professor-for-decision-and-neuroeconomic-theory-at-the-university-of-zurich/|title=Announcement NOMIS foundation|last=|first=|date=|website=The NOMIS Foundation|language=en-US|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-07-12}}</ref>\n\nAl\u00f3s-Ferrer has worked extensively in [[game theory]], [[bounded rationality]], [[Social choice theory|social choice]], and  [[behavioral economics]]. From 2012 to 2018, he was speaker of the interdisciplinary research unit \"Psychoeconomics,\" which used methods from psychology, economics, and neuroscience to study human decision making, and was funded by the [[Deutsche Forschungsgemeinschaft|German Research Foundation]] (DFG).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dfg.de/en/service/press/press_releases/2012/press_release_no_18/index.html|title=DFG Announcement of Funded Projects|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-07-09}}</ref>  Since January 2019, he is the editor in chief of the ''[[Journal of Economic Psychology]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iarep.org/images/2019_IAREP_Spring_newsletter_20190606.pdf|title=Newsletter IAREP|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-07-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.journals.elsevier.com/journal-of-economic-psychology|title=Journal of Economic Psychology website|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-07-09}}</ref> His research interests are [[neuroeconomics]], [[decision theory]], [[game theory]], evolution and learning in games and markets.\n\n== Selected publications ==\n\n* Al\u00f3s-Ferrer, Carlos (2018). ''A Review Essay on Social Neuroscience: Can Research on the Social Brain and Economics Inform Each Other?'', '''Journal of Economic Literature''', 56 (1), pp.&nbsp;234\u2013264.\n* Al\u00f3s-Ferrer, Carlos and Klaus Ritzberger (2016). ''The Theory of Extensive Form Games''. Springer-Verlag Berlin Heidelberg. {{ISBN|978-3-662-49942-9}}.\n* Achtziger, Anja and Carlos Al\u00f3s-Ferrer (2014). ''Fast or Rational? A Response-Times Study of Bayesian Updating'', '''Management Science''', 60 (4), pp.&nbsp;923\u2013938.\n* Achtziger, Anja, Carlos Al\u00f3s-Ferrer, Sabine H\u00fcgelsch\u00e4fer, and Marco Steinhauser (2014). ''The Neural Basis of Belief Updating and Rational Decision Making'', '''Social Cognitive and Affective Neuroscience''', 9 (1), pp.&nbsp;55\u201362.\n* Al\u00f3s-Ferrer, Carlos and Nick Netzer (2010). ''The Logit-Response Dynamics'', '''Games and Economic Behavior''', 68 (2), pp.&nbsp;413\u2013427.\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [https://www.econ.uzh.ch/en/people/faculty/alos-ferrer.html University of Zurich, personal webpage].\n\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:University of Zurich faculty]]\n", "name_user": "RAlex42", "label": "safe", "comment": "Broken Link for CV PDF.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carlos_Al%C3%B3s-Ferrer"}
{"title_page": "Omurtag (town)", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement <!--more fields are available for this Infobox--See Template:Infobox Settlement-->\n|official_name = Omurtag\n|image_skyline=Omurtag-ot-Panicishte.jpg\n|image_caption=View of Omurtag\n|subdivision_type = [[Countries of the world|Country]]\n|subdivision_name       = [[Bulgaria]]\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Provinces of Bulgaria|Province]]<br><small>(Oblast)</small>\n|timezone=[[Eastern European Time|EET]]\n|utc_offset=+2\n|timezone_DST=[[Eastern European Summer Time|EEST]]\n|utc_offset_DST=+3\n|image_seal = Emblem of Omurtag.png|\n|map_caption = Location of Omurtag, Bulgaria|\n|pushpin_map            =Bulgaria <!-- the name of a location map as per http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Location_map -->\n|pushpin_label_position = <!-- the position of the pushpin label: left, right, top, bottom, none -->\n|pushpin_map_caption    =Location of Omurtag, Bulgaria\n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|leader_title           =Mayor\n|postal_code_type       =[[List of postal codes in Bulgaria|Postal Code]]\n|\n|\nnative_name=\u041e\u043c\u0443\u0440\u0442\u0430\u0433|\nimage_shield=|\nsubdivision_name1=[[Targovishte Province|Targovishte]]|\npopulation_total=7,369|population_urban=24876|population_footnotes=<ref name=\"census 2011-targovishte\"/>|\npopulation_as_of=<small>Census February 2011</small>|\nelevation_m=525|\npostal_code=7900|\narea_code=0605\n|coordinates            = {{coord|43|6|0|N|26|25|1.2|E|region:BG|display=inline,title}}\n|leader_name=|\n}}\n\n'''Omurtag''' ({{Lang-bg|\u041e\u043c\u0443\u0440\u0442\u0430\u0433}}) is a town at the eastern foot of [[Stara Planina]] in northeastern [[Bulgaria]], part of [[Targovishte Province]], situated at 525 m above sea level. It is the administrative centre of the homonymous [[Omurtag Municipality]]. As of February 2011, the town has a population of 7,369 inhabitants.<ref name=\"census 2011-targovishte\">{{in lang|bg}} [http://www.nsi.bg/census2011/pagebg2.php?p2=36&sp2=134&SSPP2=146 Bulgarian National Statistical Institute - Targovishte Province - Census 2011] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110511000734/http://www.nsi.bg/census2011/pagebg2.php?p2=36&sp2=134&SSPP2=146 |date=11 May 2011 }}</ref>\n\nA notable natives are [[Aleksandr Panayotov Aleksandrov|Aleksandar Aleksandrov]], one of the two [[Timeline of astronauts by nationality|Bulgarian cosmonauts]], and [[Viktor Yosifov]], captain of the [[Bulgaria men's national volleyball team]].\n\n== History ==\n[[Image:Carkvata-Omurtag.jpg|left|thumb|200px|The 1860 [[St Demetrius]] the Megalomartyr [[Bulgarian Orthodox]] church in Omurtag.]]\n[[File:000400gmtma2ddkfm1dzc2 - Omurtag city hall.jpg|left|thumb|200px|City hall]]\nThe area around the modern town has been inhabited since the [[Neolithic]]. Part of [[Justinian I]]'s defensive system in the 6th century, the region gained importance as part of the [[First Bulgarian Empire]] due to the proximity to the capitals [[Pliska]] and [[Preslav]] and the passes of Stara Planina.\n\nThe first written evidence of the modern town dates from the 17th century, when it was mentioned as the [[qadaa|kaza]] centre ''Osman Pazar\u0131'' in [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] tax registers. The settlement was a centre of craftsmanship and trade. \n\nOsman Pazar\u0131 was liberated from [[History of Ottoman Bulgaria|Ottoman rule]] on 27 January 1878 by [[Russia]]n troops under [[Johann Casimir Ehrnrooth]] during the [[Russo-Turkish War, 1877-78|Russo-Turkish War of 1877-78]]. Most of the Turkish inhabitants of the town left and were replaced by Bulgarians from around [[Tran, Bulgaria|Tran]] and [[Kyustendil]]. \n\nOmurtag acquired its present name in 1934, named after the Bulgarian [[Khan (title)|khan]] [[Omortag of Bulgaria|Omurtag]].\n\n[[File:Historical Museum - Omurtag.jpg|thumb|Historical Museum]]\n\n==Population==\n\n<!--THIS TABLE IS STANDARD TO ALL BULGARIAN CITIES ARTICLES. PLEASE LEAVE -->\n{{Table BG town population\n| city = Omurtag\n| 1887 = no data\n| 1910 = no data\n| 1934 = no data\n| 1946 = 4,233\n| 1956 = 6,127\n| 1965 = 8,161\n| 1975 = 9,082\n| 1985 = 9,505\n| 1992 = 8,941\n| 2001 = 8,893\n| 2005 = 8,867\n| 2007 = 8,902\n| 2009 = 8,725\n| 2011 = 7,369\n| highest number = 10,160\n| highest year = 1980\n| ref 1 = <ref name=\"census 2011-targovishte\"/><ref name=\"statistika\">{{in lang|en}} [http://www.nsi.bg/otrasalen.php?otr=53&a1=1583&a2=1584&a3=1588#cont Bulgarian National Statistical Institute - Bulgarian towns in 2009]</ref><ref name=\"pop1992\">{{in lang|bg}}[http://statlib.nsi.bg:8181/isisbgstat/ssp/lister.asp?content=/Fullt/extpages/DN_21_2_1992_1994/DN_21_2_1992_1994_P*.pdf&from=1&to=282&index=&cont=/Fullt/extpages/DN_21_2_1992_1994/DN_21_2_1992_1994_content.pdf&type=%F1%F2%F0%E0%ED%E8%F6%E8 National Statistical Institute - Towns population 1956-1992]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n| ref 2 = <ref name=\"population\">{{in lang|en}} [http://www.citypopulation.de/Bulgaria-Cities.html \u201eWorldCityPopulation\u201c]</ref>\n| ref 3 = <ref name=\"pop-stat\">[http://pop-stat.mashke.org/bulgaria-cities.htm \u201epop-stat.mashke.org\u201c]</ref>\n| ref 4 = <ref name=\"BAN\">{{in lang|bg}} [http://www.geography.iit.bas.bg/2009/1-09/13-17.pdf Bulgarian Academy of Sciences] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706142758/http://www.geography.iit.bas.bg/2009/1-09/13-17.pdf |date=6 July 2011 }}</ref>\n}}\n\n== Notable people ==\n*[[Aleksandr Panayotov Aleksandrov]] - retired Bulgarian cosmonaut\n*[[Daki Yordanov]] - Bulgarian botanist and university lecturer, academician of the Bulgarian Academy of Sciences.\n*[[Dimitar Petkov]] - Bulgarian teacher, leading member of the Bulgarian People's Liberal Party\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{in lang|bg}}[https://web.archive.org/web/20100727112842/http://www.omurtag.bg/ Official municipality cite]\n\n{{Cities in Bulgaria}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Omurtag (Town)}}\n[[Category:Towns in Bulgaria]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Targovishte Province]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement <!--more fields are available for this Infobox--See Template:Infobox Settlement-->\n|official_name = Omurtag\n|image_skyline=Omurtag-ot-Panicishte.jpg\n|image_caption=View of Omurtag\n|subdivision_type = [[Countries of the world|Country]]\n|subdivision_name       = [[Bulgaria]]\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Provinces of Bulgaria|Province]]<br><small>(Oblast)</small>\n|timezone=[[Eastern European Time|EET]]\n|utc_offset=+2\n|timezone_DST=[[Eastern European Summer Time|EEST]]\n|utc_offset_DST=+3\n|image_seal = Emblem of Omurtag.png|\n|map_caption = Location of Omurtag, Bulgaria|\n|pushpin_map            =Bulgaria <!-- the name of a location map as per http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Location_map -->\n|pushpin_label_position = <!-- the position of the pushpin label: left, right, top, bottom, none -->\n|pushpin_map_caption    =Location of Omurtag, Bulgaria\n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|leader_title           =Mayor\n|postal_code_type       =[[List of postal codes in Bulgaria|Postal Code]]\n|\n|\nnative_name=\u041e\u043c\u0443\u0440\u0442\u0430\u0433|\nimage_shield=|\nsubdivision_name1=[[Targovishte Province|Targovishte]]|\npopulation_total=7,369|population_urban=24876|population_footnotes=<ref name=\"census 2011-targovishte\"/>|\npopulation_as_of=<small>Census February 2011</small>|\nelevation_m=525|\npostal_code=7900|\narea_code=0605\n|coordinates            = {{coord|43|6|0|N|26|25|1.2|E|region:BG|display=inline,title}}\n|leader_name=|\n}}\n\n'''Omurtag''' ({{Lang-bg|\u041e\u043c\u0443\u0440\u0442\u0430\u0433}}) is a town at the eastern foot of [[Stara Planina]] in northeastern [[Bulgaria]], part of [[Targovishte Province]], situated at 525 m above sea level. It is the administrative centre of the homonymous [[Omurtag Municipality]]. As of February 2011, the town has a population of 7,369 inhabitants.<ref name=\"census 2011-targovishte\">{{in lang|bg}} [http://www.nsi.bg/census2011/pagebg2.php?p2=36&sp2=134&SSPP2=146 Bulgarian National Statistical Institute - Targovishte Province - Census 2011] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110511000734/http://www.nsi.bg/census2011/pagebg2.php?p2=36&sp2=134&SSPP2=146 |date=11 May 2011 }}</ref>\n\nA notable natives are [[Aleksandr Panayotov Aleksandrov|Aleksandar Aleksandrov]], one of the two [[Timeline of astronauts by nationality|Bulgarian cosmonauts]], and [[Viktor Yosifov]], captain of the [[Bulgaria men's national volleyball team]].\n\n== History ==\n[[Image:Carkvata-Omurtag.jpg|left|thumb|200px|The 1860 [[St Demetrius]] the Megalomartyr [[Bulgarian Orthodox]] church in Omurtag.]]\n[[File:000400gmtma2ddkfm1dzc2 - Omurtag city hall.jpg|left|thumb|200px|City hall]]\nThe area around the modern town has been inhabited since the [[Neolithic]]. Part of [[Justinian I]]'s defensive system in the 6th century, the region gained importance as part of the [[First Bulgarian Empire]] due to the proximity to the capitals [[Pliska]] and [[Preslav]] and the passes of Stara Planina.\n\nThe first written evidence of the modern town dates from the 17th century, when it was mentioned as the [[qadaa|kaza]] centre ''Osman Pazar\u0131'' in [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] tax registers. The settlement was a centre of craftsmanship and trade. \n\nOsman Pazar\u0131 was liberated from [[History of Ottoman Bulgaria|Ottoman rule]] on 27 January 1878 by [[Russia]]n troops under [[Johann Casimir Ehrnrooth]] during the [[Russo-Turkish War, 1877-78|Russo-Turkish War of 1877-78]]. Most of the Turkish inhabitants of the town left and were replaced by Bulgarians from around [[Tran, Bulgaria|Tran]] and [[Kyustendil]]. \n\nOmurtag acquired its present name in 1934, named after the Bulgarian [[Khan (title)|khan]] [[Omortag of Bulgaria|Omurtag]].\n\n[[File:Historical Museum - Omurtag.jpg|thumb|Historical Museum]]\n\n==Population==\n\n<!--THIS TABLE IS