{"title_page": "Joseph Safra", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Joseph Safra\n| image              = Joseph Safra Portrait Painting Collage By Danor Shtruzman.jpg\n| caption            = \n| birth_date         = {{birth year and age|1938}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/the-story-behind-the-safras-bankings-most-mysterious-family-2012-6?op=1|title=The Safra Dynasty: The Mysterious Family of the Richest Banker in the World|website=businessinsider.com|accessdate=17 August 2018}}</ref>\n| birth_place        = [[Beirut]], [[Lebanon]]<ref>''[https://www.familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:V1S7-YCM Joseph Safra] (1956)'', information from the National Archives, Rio de Janeiro. Scan of Joseph Safra's Brazilian entry visa on 1956 on familysearch.org</ref><ref name=\"bloomberg.com2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/billionaires/profiles/joseph-y-safra/|title=Bloomberg Billionaires Index - Joseph Safra|accessdate=24 April 2019|via=www.bloomberg.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.artnews.com/top200/joseph-safra/|title=Joseph Safra -|last=arielhauter|website=ARTnews|accessdate=24 April 2019}}</ref>\n| nationality        = [[Lebanese people|Lebanese]] [[Brazilians|Brazilian]] <ref>''[https://www.familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:V1S7-YCM Joseph Safra] (1956)'', information from the National Archives, Rio de Janeiro. Scan of Joseph Safra's Brazilian entry visa on 1956 on familysearch.org</ref> \n| education          = \n| organization       = Safra\u2019s banks\n| spouse             = Vicky Sarfati\n| children           = 4<ref name=\"ForbesBillionaires2\" />\n| parents            = [[Jacob Safra]] (father)\n| family             = [[Moise Safra]] (brother)<br> [[Edmond Safra]] (brother)<br> [[Lily Safra]] (sister-in-law)\n| known_for          = The richest banker in the world by Forbes magazine.<ref>https://www.jta.org/quick-reads/jewish-philanthropist-becomes-brazils-richest-person</ref>\n| net_worth          = US$24.7 billion (June 2019)<br/><ref name=\"ForbesBillionaires2\" />\n}}\n\n'''Joseph Safra''' ({{lang-ar|\u064a\u0648\u0633\u0641 \u0635\u0641\u0631\u0627}} ; born 1938) is a Brazilian of Lebanese origin<ref>''[https://www.familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:V1S7-YCM Joseph Safra] (1956)'', information from the National Archives, Rio de Janeiro. Scan of Joseph Safra's Brazilian entry visa on 1954 on familysearch.org</ref><ref name=\"bloomberg.com2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/billionaires/profiles/joseph-y-safra/|title=Bloomberg Billionaires Index - Joseph Safra|accessdate=24 April 2019|via=www.bloomberg.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.artnews.com/top200/joseph-safra/|title=Joseph Safra -|last=arielhauter|website=ARTnews|accessdate=24 April 2019}}</ref> [[billionaire]] banker who runs the Brazilian banking and investment empire, [[Safra Group]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/joseph-safra/|title=Joseph Safra|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2019-02-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/tosv2.html?vid=&uuid=49ca45f0-2bc7-11e9-a5f8-ab58a7b5d53f&url=L2JpbGxpb25haXJlcy9wcm9maWxlcy9qb3NlcGgteS1zYWZyYS8=|title=Bloomberg - Are you a robot?|website=www.bloomberg.com|access-date=2019-02-08}}</ref> He is the chairman of all Safra companies, among them [[Safra National Bank of New York]] and [[Banco Safra]] headquartered in [[S\u00e3o Paulo]], Brazil.<ref name=\"ForbesBillionaires2\">[https://www.forbes.com/profile/joseph-safra/ Forbes: The World's Billionaires - Joseph Safra] November 2014</ref> Safra has a net worth of $24.7 billion.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/joseph-safra/|title=Joseph Safra|work=Forbes|access-date=13 July 2017|language=en}}</ref> He is of [[Lebanese Jews|Lebanese Jewish]] origin, and comes from the Safra family.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jpost.com/Jewish-World/Jewish-Features/The-worlds-50-Richest-Jews-11-20|title=The world's 50 Richest Jews: 11-20|website=jpost.com|accessdate=17 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nJoseph Safra was born in [[Beirut]], [[Lebanon]]<ref>''[https://www.familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:V1S7-YCM Joseph Safra] (1956)'', information from the National Archives, Rio de Janeiro. Scan of Joseph Safra's Brazilian entry visa on 1956 on familysearch.org</ref><ref name=\"bloomberg.com2\" /><ref name=\"auto2\" /> to a [[Sephardi Jews|Sephardic Jewish]] family with banking connections dating back to [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] times,<ref name=\"cityamkaspira2\">Kasmira Jefford, [http://www.cityam.com/1415669320/brazil-s-safra-feasts-gherkin-tower Gherkin bought by Safra Group: Meet the Brazilian-Lebanese billionaire behind the \u00a3700m deal], ''[[City A.M.]]'', 11 November 2014</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/meet-joseph-safra-the-richest-banker-on-the-planet-2012-3?r=US&IR=T&IR=T|title=Meet Joseph Safra, The Richest Banker on the Planet|website=Business Insider}}</ref> and grew up in [[Beirut]], Lebanon.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1999/12/08/business/international-business-the-safras-of-brazil-banking-faith-and-security.html?pagewanted=2&src=pm New York Times: \"INTERNATIONAL BUSINESS; The Safras of Brazil: Banking, Faith and Security\" By SIMON ROMERO] 8 December 1999</ref> The family's history in banking originated with caravan trade between Beirut, Aleppo, [[Alexandria]] and [[Istanbul]] during the [[Ottoman Empire]].\n\nThe Safra family moved to Brazil in 1952. In 1955, Joseph's 23-year-old brother, [[Edmond Safra]], and his father, [[Jacob Safra]], started working in Brazil by financing assets in S\u00e3o Paulo. But soon, Edmond Safra separated from his brothers Joseph and Moise and headed to New York where he founded the Republic National Bank of New York (which he later sold to [[HSBC]] in 1999 and donated most of his money to the Edmond Safra Foundation). Joseph Safra founded [[Banco Safra]] in 1955 and today it is reportedly the 6th largest private bank in Brazil. He remains the chairman of the [[Safra Group]] offering banking services throughout Europe, North and South America.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/tosv2.html?vid=&uuid=aa79b520-2bc7-11e9-94c3-99814737c66d&url=L2JpbGxpb25haXJlcy9wcm9maWxlcy9qb3NlcGgteS1zYWZyYS8=|title=Bloomberg - Bloomberg Billionaires Index|website=www.bloomberg.com|access-date=2019-02-08}}</ref>\n\nJoseph Safra acquired the remaining shares of Safra Group companies from his brother [[Moise Safra]]. The two brothers maintain a shareholding in [[Fibria| Fibria Cellulose]].\n\n==Personal life==\nHe has four children: [[Jacob J. Safra]], {{Interlanguage link multi|Esther Safra|pt}} (married to {{Interlanguage link multi|Carlos Dayan|pt}}, son of [[Sasson Dayan]]), Alberto J. Safra, David J. Safra.<ref name=JVCourt>{{Cite web|title=Court Accepts Charges Against Brazil Banker Joseph Safra   |publisher=[[Jewish Voice]]|date=27 April 2016 |url= http://thejewishvoice.com/2016/04/27/court-accepts-charges-against-brazil-banker-joseph-safra/ }}</ref> Jacob is responsible for all international operations outside of Brazil while David and Alberto, manage Banco Safra in Brazil.<ref name=JVCourt />\n\n== Property ==\nIn 2013, Joseph Safra's family acquired more than a dozen properties in the U.S., primarily in New York City. They also own a portfolio of commercial real estate in Brazil.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/joseph-safra/|title=Joseph Safra|work=Forbes|access-date=13 March 2017|language=en}}</ref> In 2014 Safra paid more than \u00a3700 million to buy [[30 St Mary Axe|The Gherkin]] \u2013 one of the most distinctive towers in the City of London.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-4271050/Chinas-CC-Land-buys-London-skyscraper-1-15-bln-pounds.html#ixzz4air02N5h|title=China's CC Land buys London's cheesegrater for \u00a31.15 billion|work=Mail Online|access-date=13 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/1c1c5a9c-68be-11e4-af00-00144feabdc0|title=Safra snaps up the Gherkin for \u00a3726m|website=www.ft.com|language=en-GB|access-date=13 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Business holdings==\n*[[Fibria|Fibria Cellulose]]\n*[[Chiquita]]\n*[[Safra Group]]\n**[[Banco Safra]]\n**[[J. Safra Sarasin]]\n**[[Safra National Bank of New York]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.forbes.com/finance/lists/10/2004/LIR.jhtml?passListId=10&passYear=2004&passListType=Person&uniqueId=3TSL&datatype=Person Forbes World's Richest People]\n*[http://www.businessinsider.com/meet-joseph-safra-the-richest-banker-on-the-planet-2012-3 Meet Joseph Safra, The Richest Banker On The Planet] and [http://www.businessinsider.com/the-story-behind-the-safras-bankings-most-mysterious-family-2012-6 The Safra Dynasty: The Mysterious Family Of The Richest Banker In The World] on [[Business Insider]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Safra, Joseph}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Brazilian Jews]]\n[[Category:20th-century Sephardi Jews]]\n[[Category:21st-century Sephardi Jews]]\n[[Category:Brazilian bankers]]\n[[Category:Brazilian billionaires]]\n[[Category:Safra family]]\n[[Category:Syrian emigrants to Brazil]]\n[[Category:Brazilian people of Lebanese-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Brazilian people of Syrian-Jewish descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Joseph Safra\n| image              = Joseph Safra Portrait Painting Collage By Danor Shtruzman.jpg\n| caption            = \n| birth_date         = {{birth year and age|1938}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/the-story-behind-the-safras-bankings-most-mysterious-family-2012-6?op=1|title=The Safra Dynasty: The Mysterious Family of the Richest Banker in the World|website=businessinsider.com|accessdate=17 August 2018}}</ref>\n| birth_place        = [[Beirut]], [[Lebanon]]<ref>''[https://www.familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:V1S7-YCM Joseph Safra] (1956)'', information from the National Archives, Rio de Janeiro. Scan of Joseph Safra's Brazilian entry visa on 1956 on familysearch.org</ref><ref name=\"bloomberg.com2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/billionaires/profiles/joseph-y-safra/|title=Bloomberg Billionaires Index - Joseph Safra|accessdate=24 April 2019|via=www.bloomberg.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.artnews.com/top200/joseph-safra/|title=Joseph Safra -|last=arielhauter|website=ARTnews|accessdate=24 April 2019}}</ref>\n| nationality        = [[Lebanese]] [[Brazilian]] <ref>''[https://www.familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:V1S7-YCM Joseph Safra] (1956)'', information from the National Archives, Rio de Janeiro. Scan of Joseph Safra's Brazilian entry visa on 1956 on familysearch.org</ref> \n| education          = \n| organization       = Safra\u2019s banks\n| spouse             = Vicky Sarfati\n| children           = 4<ref name=\"ForbesBillionaires2\" />\n| parents            = [[Jacob Safra]] (father)\n| family             = [[Moise Safra]] (brother)<br> [[Edmond Safra]] (brother)<br> [[Lily Safra]] (sister-in-law)\n| known_for          = The richest banker in the world by Forbes magazine.<ref>https://www.jta.org/quick-reads/jewish-philanthropist-becomes-brazils-richest-person</ref>\n| net_worth          = US$24.7 billion (June 2019)<br/><ref name=\"ForbesBillionaires2\" />\n}}\n\n'''Joseph Safra''' ({{lang-ar|\u064a\u0648\u0633\u0641 \u0635\u0641\u0631\u0627}} ; born 1938) is a Brazilian of Lebanese origin<ref>''[https://www.familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:V1S7-YCM Joseph Safra] (1956)'', information from the National Archives, Rio de Janeiro. Scan of Joseph Safra's Brazilian entry visa on 1954 on familysearch.org</ref><ref name=\"bloomberg.com2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/billionaires/profiles/joseph-y-safra/|title=Bloomberg Billionaires Index - Joseph Safra|accessdate=24 April 2019|via=www.bloomberg.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.artnews.com/top200/joseph-safra/|title=Joseph Safra -|last=arielhauter|website=ARTnews|accessdate=24 April 2019}}</ref> [[billionaire]] banker who runs the Brazilian banking and investment empire, [[Safra Group]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/joseph-safra/|title=Joseph Safra|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2019-02-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/tosv2.html?vid=&uuid=49ca45f0-2bc7-11e9-a5f8-ab58a7b5d53f&url=L2JpbGxpb25haXJlcy9wcm9maWxlcy9qb3NlcGgteS1zYWZyYS8=|title=Bloomberg - Are you a robot?|website=www.bloomberg.com|access-date=2019-02-08}}</ref> He is the chairman of all Safra companies, among them [[Safra National Bank of New York]] and [[Banco Safra]] headquartered in [[S\u00e3o Paulo]], Brazil.<ref name=\"ForbesBillionaires2\">[https://www.forbes.com/profile/joseph-safra/ Forbes: The World's Billionaires - Joseph Safra] November 2014</ref> Safra has a net worth of $24.7 billion.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/joseph-safra/|title=Joseph Safra|work=Forbes|access-date=13 July 2017|language=en}}</ref> He is of [[Lebanese Jews|Lebanese Jewish]] origin, and comes from the Safra family.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jpost.com/Jewish-World/Jewish-Features/The-worlds-50-Richest-Jews-11-20|title=The world's 50 Richest Jews: 11-20|website=jpost.com|accessdate=17 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nJoseph Safra was born in [[Beirut]], [[Lebanon]]<ref>''[https://www.familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:V1S7-YCM Joseph Safra] (1956)'', information from the National Archives, Rio de Janeiro. Scan of Joseph Safra's Brazilian entry visa on 1956 on familysearch.org</ref><ref name=\"bloomberg.com2\" /><ref name=\"auto2\" /> to a [[Sephardi Jews|Sephardic Jewish]] family with banking connections dating back to [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] times,<ref name=\"cityamkaspira2\">Kasmira Jefford, [http://www.cityam.com/1415669320/brazil-s-safra-feasts-gherkin-tower Gherkin bought by Safra Group: Meet the Brazilian-Lebanese billionaire behind the \u00a3700m deal], ''[[City A.M.]]'', 11 November 2014</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/meet-joseph-safra-the-richest-banker-on-the-planet-2012-3?r=US&IR=T&IR=T|title=Meet Joseph Safra, The Richest Banker on the Planet|website=Business Insider}}</ref> and grew up in [[Beirut]], Lebanon.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1999/12/08/business/international-business-the-safras-of-brazil-banking-faith-and-security.html?pagewanted=2&src=pm New York Times: \"INTERNATIONAL BUSINESS; The Safras of Brazil: Banking, Faith and Security\" By SIMON ROMERO] 8 December 1999</ref> The family's history in banking originated with caravan trade between Beirut, Aleppo, [[Alexandria]] and [[Istanbul]] during the [[Ottoman Empire]].\n\nThe Safra family moved to Brazil in 1952. In 1955, Joseph's 23-year-old brother, [[Edmond Safra]], and his father, [[Jacob Safra]], started working in Brazil by financing assets in S\u00e3o Paulo. But soon, Edmond Safra separated from his brothers Joseph and Moise and headed to New York where he founded the Republic National Bank of New York (which he later sold to [[HSBC]] in 1999 and donated most of his money to the Edmond Safra Foundation). Joseph Safra founded [[Banco Safra]] in 1955 and today it is reportedly the 6th largest private bank in Brazil. He remains the chairman of the [[Safra Group]] offering banking services throughout Europe, North and South America.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/tosv2.html?vid=&uuid=aa79b520-2bc7-11e9-94c3-99814737c66d&url=L2JpbGxpb25haXJlcy9wcm9maWxlcy9qb3NlcGgteS1zYWZyYS8=|title=Bloomberg - Bloomberg Billionaires Index|website=www.bloomberg.com|access-date=2019-02-08}}</ref>\n\nJoseph Safra acquired the remaining shares of Safra Group companies from his brother [[Moise Safra]]. The two brothers maintain a shareholding in [[Fibria| Fibria Cellulose]].\n\n==Personal life==\nHe has four children: [[Jacob J. Safra]], {{Interlanguage link multi|Esther Safra|pt}} (married to {{Interlanguage link multi|Carlos Dayan|pt}}, son of [[Sasson Dayan]]), Alberto J. Safra, David J. Safra.<ref name=JVCourt>{{Cite web|title=Court Accepts Charges Against Brazil Banker Joseph Safra   |publisher=[[Jewish Voice]]|date=27 April 2016 |url= http://thejewishvoice.com/2016/04/27/court-accepts-charges-against-brazil-banker-joseph-safra/ }}</ref> Jacob is responsible for all international operations outside of Brazil while David and Alberto, manage Banco Safra in Brazil.<ref name=JVCourt />\n\n== Property ==\nIn 2013, Joseph Safra's family acquired more than a dozen properties in the U.S., primarily in New York City. They also own a portfolio of commercial real estate in Brazil.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/joseph-safra/|title=Joseph Safra|work=Forbes|access-date=13 March 2017|language=en}}</ref> In 2014 Safra paid more than \u00a3700 million to buy [[30 St Mary Axe|The Gherkin]] \u2013 one of the most distinctive towers in the City of London.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-4271050/Chinas-CC-Land-buys-London-skyscraper-1-15-bln-pounds.html#ixzz4air02N5h|title=China's CC Land buys London's cheesegrater for \u00a31.15 billion|work=Mail Online|access-date=13 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/1c1c5a9c-68be-11e4-af00-00144feabdc0|title=Safra snaps up the Gherkin for \u00a3726m|website=www.ft.com|language=en-GB|access-date=13 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Business holdings==\n*[[Fibria|Fibria Cellulose]]\n*[[Chiquita]]\n*[[Safra Group]]\n**[[Banco Safra]]\n**[[J. Safra Sarasin]]\n**[[Safra National Bank of New York]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.forbes.com/finance/lists/10/2004/LIR.jhtml?passListId=10&passYear=2004&passListType=Person&uniqueId=3TSL&datatype=Person Forbes World's Richest People]\n*[http://www.businessinsider.com/meet-joseph-safra-the-richest-banker-on-the-planet-2012-3 Meet Joseph Safra, The Richest Banker On The Planet] and [http://www.businessinsider.com/the-story-behind-the-safras-bankings-most-mysterious-family-2012-6 The Safra Dynasty: The Mysterious Family Of The Richest Banker In The World] on [[Business Insider]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Safra, Joseph}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Brazilian Jews]]\n[[Category:20th-century Sephardi Jews]]\n[[Category:21st-century Sephardi Jews]]\n[[Category:Brazilian bankers]]\n[[Category:Brazilian billionaires]]\n[[Category:Safra family]]\n[[Category:Syrian emigrants to Brazil]]\n[[Category:Brazilian people of Lebanese-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Brazilian people of Syrian-Jewish descent]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:Lebanese\u2192Lebanese people,Brazilian\u2192Brazilians", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joseph_Safra"}
{"title_page": "Kavarna", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox settlement <!--more fields are available for this Infobox--See Template:Infobox Settlement-->\n|official_name = Kavarna\n|subdivision_type = [[Countries of the world|Country]]\n|subdivision_name       = [[Bulgaria]]\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Provinces of Bulgaria|Province]]<br><small>(Oblast)</small>\n|timezone=[[Eastern European Time|EET]]\n|image_shield=BGR \u041a\u0430\u0432\u0430\u0440\u043d\u0430 COA.png\n|utc_offset=+2\n|timezone_DST=[[Eastern European Summer Time|EEST]]\n|utc_offset_DST=+3\n|image_skyline = Kavarna Bulgaria aerial photo from the Black Sea.jpg\n|map_caption = Location of Kavarna|\n|pushpin_map            =Bulgaria <!-- the name of a location map as per http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Location_map -->\n|pushpin_label_position = <!-- the position of the pushpin label: left, right, top, bottom, none -->\n|pushpin_map_caption    =Location of Kavarna\n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|leader_title           =Mayor\n|postal_code_type       =[[List of postal codes in Bulgaria|Postal Code]]\n|\n|\nsubdivision_name1=[[Dobrich Province|Dobrich]]|\npopulation_total=11,397|population_urban=15834|population_footnotes=<ref name=\"statistika\"/><ref name=\"population\"/><ref name=\"pop-stat\"/>|\npopulation_as_of=31.12.2009|\nelevation_m=121|\npostal_code=9650|\narea_code=+359 570\n|coordinates            = {{coord|43|26|N|28|20|E|region:BG|display=inline,title}}\n|leader_name=[[Nina Stavreva]]|\n}}\n\n'''Kavarna''' ({{lang-bg|\u041a\u0430\u0432\u0430\u0440\u043d\u0430}}, is a [[Bulgarian Black Sea Coast|Black Sea coastal]] town and [[seaside resort]] in the [[Dobruja]] region of northeastern [[Bulgaria]]. It lies {{convert|64|km|0|abbr=off}} northeast of [[Varna]], {{convert|49|km|0|abbr=on}} from [[Dobrich]] on the international road E87 and {{convert|43|km|0|abbr=on}} south of the border with [[Romania]]. It is the principal town of [[Kavarna Municipality]], part of [[Dobrich Province]]. As of December 2009, the town has a population of 11,397 inhabitants.<ref name=\"statistika\">{{in lang|en}} [http://www.nsi.bg/otrasalen.php?otr=53&a1=1583&a2=1584&a3=1588#cont Bulgarian National Statistical Institute - towns in 2009] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101113165731/http://www.nsi.bg/otrasalen.php?otr=53&a1=1583&a2=1584&a3=1588#cont |date=2010-11-13 }}</ref><ref name=\"population\">{{in lang|en}} [http://www.citypopulation.de/Bulgaria-Cities.html \u201eWorldCityPopulation\u201c]</ref><ref name=\"pop-stat\">[http://pop-stat.mashke.org/bulgaria-cities.htm \u201epop-stat.mashke.org\u201c]</ref> A little yacht port, a fishing base, a spacious beach and a resort complex exist in the town. The landmark Cape [[Kaliakra]] is located a few kilometers to the east, as is the tiny beachfront resort of [[Rusalka, Bulgaria|Rusalka]]. Three 18-hole [[golf courses]] with villa communities and marinas are being developed nearby, two of the courses are designed by [[Gary Player]] and one by [[Ian Woosnam]].\n\nDuring the 2000s, the town became famous with the annual [[Kaliakra Rock Fest]] featuring famous rock bands from around the world.\n\n==Etymology==\nWith the Bulgarian conquest in the 7th century AD, the name ''Karvuna'' replaced the similarly-sounding ancient Greek ''Krounoi'' as the then name of the neighboring modern town of [[Balchik]]; the names ''Karvunska Hora'' and ''Principality of Karvuna'' were related to that town, which was also mentioned on 14th-century Italian [[portolan charts]] with the Italianized form ''Carbona''.\n\nThe name ''Kavarna'' as referring to this city was first mentioned in the 15th century; perhaps it was a new name influenced phonetically by the preexisting names of Karvuna (which town was already known as Balchik) and Varna.\n\n==Geography==\nThe lay of the land is flat and the seacoast of Kavarna is {{convert|42|km|0|abbr=on}} long. Along it there are small beaches, including an artificial one. Gore Chirakman with its almost sheer slopes towers above the seacoast. Remains of stronghold walls, moats, buildings, churches and [[necropolis]]es can be found on the flat [[plateau]]. The region is rich in mineral waters.\n\nThe area around Kavarna offers opportunities for developing ecotourism and specialized tourism&nbsp;\u2014 examination and photography of plants, dolphins and various kinds of fish in the coastal waters. The variety of birds attracts tourists from all parts of the world and contributes to Kaliakra and Yaylata becoming one of the most preferred places in Bulgaria for the development of ornithological tourism.\n\n==Population==\n\n<!--THIS TABLE IS STANDARD TO ALL BULGARIAN CITIES ARTICLES. PLEASE LEAVE -->\n{{Table BG town population\n| city = Kavarna\n| 1887 = no data\n| 1910 = no data\n| 1934 = no data\n| 1946 = 5,652\n| 1956 = 7,053\n| 1965 = 8,300\n| 1975 = 10,881\n| 1985 = 12,033\n| 1992 = 12,139\n| 2001 = 11,479\n| 2005 = 11,415\n| 2007 = 11,438\n| 2009 = 11,397\n| ref 1 = <ref name=\"statistika\"/>\n| ref 2 = <ref name=\"population\"/>\n| ref 3 = <ref name=\"pop-stat\"/>\n| ref 4 = <ref name=\"BAN\">{{in lang|bg}} [http://www.geography.iit.bas.bg/2009/1-09/13-17.pdf Bulgarian Academy of Sciences] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706142758/http://www.geography.iit.bas.bg/2009/1-09/13-17.pdf |date=2011-07-06 }}</ref>\n}}\n\n==History==\n[[File:Karvuna 1.jpg|left|thumb|250px|[[Kaliakra]]]]\n\nThe town was founded in the 5th century BC by [[Ancient Greece|Ancient Greek]]<ref>An Inventory of Archaic and Classical Poleis: An Investigation Conducted by The Copenhagen Polis Centre for the Danish National Research Foundation by Mogens Herman Hansen,2005,Index</ref> colonists who settled on the [[Chirakman Plateau]] in the colony '''Byzone''' (or ''Bizone'') ({{lang-grc|\u0392\u03b9\u03b6\u03ce\u03bd\u03b7}}). During the 3rd and 2nd century BC, the town played an important mediating role between the local [[Thracians|Thracian]] settlements and the Greeks. Despite being unsuitable for wharfing because of its rugged cliffs, this part of the [[Bulgarian Black Sea Coast]] was an attractive centre due to the fact that the local people produced and traded with high quality grain.\n\nDuring the second part of the 1st century BC the ancient town fell in the sea because of a disastrous earthquake. The frontal part of the Chirakman broke off and together with the richest citizens fell into the [[Black Sea]]'s waters. According to the leader of the finished first part of the underwater archaeological expedition Kavarna 2005, Asen Salkin, the Roman town of Bizone has sunk two times in the sea. For that evidence the located form skin-divers borders of a sunk residential district of the town of Bizone in Kavarna's coast. For the presence of residential buildings the archaeologists judge by the found ashlars and parts of brick walls. The finds date from the 2nd century AD. According to the leader of the expedition this residential district has nothing in common with the disastrous earthquake from the 1st century BC. The underwater finds evidence for other phenomenon, for which the scientists express only suppositions, such as transgression and regression of the strata. It has started to transgress during the 1st century AD and this has continued to the 2nd century. It is possible that during this period the coast had risen by four metres and one day it suddenly fallen through.\n\nDuring [[Ancient Rome|Roman times]] the town was restored under the same name and quickly flourished, the settlement revived and the port brightened up.\n\n[[File:Kavarna HDR.jpg|thumb|300px|View of Kavarna]]\nIn the 7th century AD the [[Slavs]] and [[Asparuh]]'s [[Bulgars]] destroyed the [[Byzantine]] town and later founded a new settlement, which entered the [[First Bulgarian Empire]]. In the late Middle Ages the settlement grew and was subject to [[Tatar]] raids; in the 14th century it became part of the [[Principality of Karvuna]], which de facto broke away from the Second Bulgarian Empire under the rule of the [[Despot (court title)|despot]]s [[Balik (Bulgarian ruler)|Balik]] and [[Dobrotitsa]] of the Bulgarian royal Terter dynasty.<ref>\u0413. \u0411\u0430\u043a\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0432, ''\u0418\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u044f \u043d\u0430 \u0431\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u0442\u0435'', \u0422\u043e\u043c 1, 2003, \u0441. 457</ref><ref>\u041f\u0435\u0442\u044a\u0440 \u041d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0432, ''\u0421\u043a\u0432\u0438\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u043a\u043d\u044f\u0437\u0435 \u041f\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0446\u0438-\u0420\u043e\u0436\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438&nbsp;\u2014 \u043a\u043b\u043e\u043d \u043d\u0430 \u0434\u0438\u043d\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438\u044f\u0442\u0430 \u0422\u0435\u0440\u0442\u0435\u0440'', online, retrieved 03-24-2007</ref>  In 1397, the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman Turks]] nearly destroyed the city, which was abandoned but resettled again and rebuilt by the early 17th century. Its present name was documented for the first time in the early 15th century.\n\nThe town was considered an economical and cultural centre during [[ancient history|Antiquity]] and the [[Middle Ages]] with rich and various remains&nbsp;\u2013 stronghold walls, early-[[Christianity|Christian]] [[basilica]], [[medieval]] [[church (building)|church]]es, and public buildings.\n\nNotable works of art, such as coins from different historical epochs, golden adornments, a golden Thracian treasure of applications, have been found in the area. Between the 15th and 19th century the town becomes popular under the name Kavarna, as a Christian settlement and port for grain export. From that time remain a Turkish bath, a medieval necropolis, a bridge, fountains, Christian churches and many inscriptions.\n\nDuring the [[Russo-Turkish War of 1877\u20131878]] Kavarna's Christian inhabitants, Bulgarians and [[Gagauz people|Gagauz]] alike, rebelled against the [[bashi-bazouk]]s and Circassian hordes. After the liberation the town became part of the [[Principality of Bulgaria]].\n\nFrom the beginning of 20th century Kavarna achieved a rapid progress as an economical and cultural centre. The town renamed ''Cavarna'' came under [[Romania]]n rule after the [[Second Balkan War]] in 1913 and again after the [[First World War]] in 1919.  This however, was met with resistance by the local Bulgarian population and its [[Internal Dobrujan Revolutionary Organisation]]. In 1940 the town was ceded back to Bulgaria by the [[Treaty of Craiova]].\n\n==Monuments and museums==\n\n===Dobruja and the Sea Display===\nThe Dobruja and the Sea Display is a small maritime museum. It is situated in an approximately restored [[Turkey|Turkish]] bath, the Hamam. It was built in the beginning of the 15th century and represents a massive beehive bath from stone, situated in the beginning of the valley leading to the port, and half a kilometre apart from the town centre. Many stone anchors, amphorae and ceramics found during the underwater archaeological expeditions are exposed there. Coins from different epochs and a golden Thracian treasure can be seen in the Treasure House Hall  The ancient and mediaeval colour painting expend our concepts for the ancient navigation around Dobruja's coasts.\n\n===Town Museum===\nThe Town Museum can be found in the building of the local library. Materials, revealing the thousand-year old history of the town are displayed in its exposition. Evidence for the life of the people in the region since ancient times are represented here. A model of prehistoric cave-dwellings, many tools, guns, rifles and pistols from the War of Liberation, as well as ethnographic materials&nbsp;\u2014 clothing, finery, folk-style cloth, are also exhibited\n\n===Ethnographic Museum===\n[[File:Dormition of the Theotokos Church - Kavarna.jpg|right|thumb|250px|Dormition of the Theotokos Church.]]\n\nThe Ethnographic Museum represents an old house from the end of the 19th century that belonged to a rich family. Its interior reveals the customs and culture of the people inhabiting that part of the country; premises typical for Dobruja houses, tools from the culture and the daily round of the people. The building is surrounded by a garden full of mulberry trees, peonies and tulips.\n\n===Churches===\nThere are two churches in the town both located in the town centre. The Church of [[Saint George]] was built in 1836 and the Dormition of the Theotokos Church in 1860. Both churches played an important role during the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] rule and after the Liberation as educational and cultural centers.\n\n===The old fountains===\nThese were 12 spring fountains situated along the valley to the port. Some of them were destroyed and the rest were restored recently. The great amount of spring water forms a small river.\n\n==Culture==\nSince 2004 the town has turned in one of the centres of musical life in Bulgaria. Kavarna has been the host to several [[Rock (music)|rock and roll]] concerts. In 2005 the most popular band to play in the town's stadium was [[Deep Purple]]. The other notable performers were mostly legends of German rock and [[heavy metal music]], such as [[Scorpions (band)|Scorpions]], [[Axel Rudi Pell]], [[Gamma Ray (band)|Gamma Ray]], [[Masterplan (band)|Masterplan]] and [[Destruction (band)|Destruction]]. On 27 August 2005 [[Accept (band)|Accept]], another German band, played here its last show with original lead vocalist [[Udo Dirkschneider]]. There is also a mural of [[Whitesnake]] singer [[David Coverdale]].\n\n2006 saw the start of the [[Kaliakra Rock Fest]] - A Metal festival (renamed to [[Kaliakra Rock Fest|Kavarna Rock Fest]] in 2010) including many metal bands. The same year followed the tradition with concerts of more metal bands as well as some pop and dance musicians. For example, Russian pop star [[Filipp Kirkorov]] sang there in September.\n\nIn 2007, performers included [[Heaven and Hell (band)|Heaven and Hell]], [[John Lawton (musician)|John Lawton]] Band, [[Manowar]], [[Mot\u00f6rhead]], [[Robert Plant]], and [[Ronnie James Dio]]. The next year saw the return of Manowar within [[Kaliakra Rock Fest]] with a 5-hour attempt to set a world record for the longest heavy metal concert. The next two days [[Alice Cooper]], [[Slayer]] and [[In Flames]] held concerts. In July 2009, [[M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce]] headlined the rock-fest, with Scorpions, [[Blind Guardian]] and [[Dream Theater]] also participating. [[Sonata Arctica]] also performed in 2008 and 2011.\n\nThe 2013 [[Volvo World Match Play Championship]] was held at the [[Thracian Cliffs Golf Course]].\n\n==International relations==\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in Poland}}\n\n===Twin towns and sister cities===\nKavarna is [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with:\n\n*{{flagicon|RUS}} [[Podolsk]], Russia<ref name=\"Podolsk twinnings\">{{cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?sourceid=navclient&hl=en&u=http%3a%2f%2fadmpodolsk.ru%2findex.php%3fcategoryid%3d126|title=Podolsk sister cities|publisher=Translate.google.com|date=|accessdate=2010-04-29}}</ref>\n\n===Honour===\n[[Kavarna Cove]] in [[Livingston Island]] in the [[South Shetland Islands]], [[Antarctica]] is named after Kavarna.\n\n==Gallery==\n{{center|<gallery>\nFile:Kavarna Bulgaria architecture.jpg|Architecture of Kavarna\nFile:Kavarna-church-mihalorel.JPG|Church in Kavarna\nFile:Dio monument.jpeg|[[Ronnie James Dio]] statue\nFile:David Coverdale Kavarna mural.png|[[David Coverdale]] mural\n</gallery>}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://www.kavarna.bg/ Official homepage]\n* [http://www.guide-bulgaria.com/NE/Dobrich/Kavarna Guide to Kavarna municipality]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070717223959/http://www.kavarnamap.eu/index_en.php Interactive map of Kavarna]\n\n{{Dobrich Province}}\n{{Bulgarian Black Sea resorts}}\n{{Kavarna}}\n{{Cities in Bulgaria}}\n\n[[Category:Towns in Bulgaria]]\n[[Category:Seaside resorts in Bulgaria]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Dobrich Province]]\n[[Category:Populated coastal places in Bulgaria]]\n[[Category:Greek colonies on the Black Sea coast]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox settlement <!--more fields are available for this Infobox--See Template:Infobox Settlement-->\n|official_name = Kavarna\n|subdivision_type = [[Countries of the world|Country]]\n|subdivision_name       = [[Bulgaria]]\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Provinces of Bulgaria|Province]]<br><small>(Oblast)</small>\n|timezone=[[Eastern European Time|EET]]\n|image_shield=BGR \u041a\u0430\u0432\u0430\u0440\u043d\u0430 COA.png\n|utc_offset=+2\n|timezone_DST=[[Eastern European Summer Time|EEST]]\n|utc_offset_DST=+3\n|image_skyline = Kavarna Bulgaria aerial photo from the Black Sea.jpg\n|map_caption = Location of Kavarna|\n|pushpin_map            =Bulgaria <!-- the name of a location map as per http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Location_map -->\n|pushpin_label_position = <!-- the position of the pushpin label: left, right, top, bottom, none -->\n|pushpin_map_caption    =Location of Kavarna\n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|leader_title           =Mayor\n|postal_code_type       =[[List of postal codes in Bulgaria|Postal Code]]\n|\n|\nsubdivision_name1=[[Dobrich Province|Dobrich]]|\npopulation_total=11,397|population_urban=15834|population_footnotes=<ref name=\"statistika\"/><ref name=\"population\"/><ref name=\"pop-stat\"/>|\npopulation_as_of=31.12.2009|\nelevation_m=121|\npostal_code=9650|\narea_code=+359 570\n|coordinates            = {{coord|43|26|N|28|20|E|region:BG|display=inline,title}}\n|leader_name=[[Nina Stavreva]]|\n}}\n\n'''Kavarna''' ({{lang-bg|\u041a\u0430\u0432\u0430\u0440\u043d\u0430}}, is a [[Bulgarian Black Sea Coast|Black Sea coastal]] town and [[seaside resort]] in the [[Dobruja]] region of northeastern [[Bulgaria]]. It lies {{convert|64|km|0|abbr=off}} northeast of [[Varna]], {{convert|49|km|0|abbr=on}} from [[Dobrich]] on the international road E87 and {{convert|43|km|0|abbr=on}} south of the border with [[Romania]]. It is the principal town of [[Kavarna Municipality]], part of [[Dobrich Province]]. As of December 2009, the town has a population of 11,397 inhabitants.<ref name=\"statistika\">{{in lang|en}} [http://www.nsi.bg/otrasalen.php?otr=53&a1=1583&a2=1584&a3=1588#cont Bulgarian National Statistical Institute - towns in 2009] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101113165731/http://www.nsi.bg/otrasalen.php?otr=53&a1=1583&a2=1584&a3=1588#cont |date=2010-11-13 }}</ref><ref name=\"population\">{{in lang|en}} [http://www.citypopulation.de/Bulgaria-Cities.html \u201eWorldCityPopulation\u201c]</ref><ref name=\"pop-stat\">[http://pop-stat.mashke.org/bulgaria-cities.htm \u201epop-stat.mashke.org\u201c]</ref> A little yacht port, a fishing base, a spacious beach and a resort complex exist in the town. The landmark Cape [[Kaliakra]] is located a few kilometers to the east, as is the tiny beachfront resort of [[Rusalka, Bulgaria|Rusalka]]. Three 18-hole [[golf courses]] with villa communities and marinas are being developed nearby, two of the courses are designed by [[Gary Player]] and one by [[Ian Woosnam]].\n\nDuring the 2000s, the town became famous with the annual [[Kaliakra Rock Fest]] featuring famous rock bands from around the world.\n\n==Etymology==\nWith the Bulgarian conquest in the 7th century AD, the name ''Karvuna'' replaced the similarly-sounding ancient Greek ''Krounoi'' as the then name of the neighboring modern town of [[Balchik]]; the names ''Karvunska Hora'' and ''Principality of Karvuna'' were related to that town, which was also mentioned on 14th-century Italian [[portolan charts]] with the Italianized form ''Carbona''.\n\nThe name ''Kavarna'' as referring to this city was first mentioned in the 15th century; perhaps it was a new name influenced phonetically by the preexisting names of Karvuna (which town was already known as Balchik) and Varna.\n\n==Geography==\nThe lay of the land is flat and the seacoast of Kavarna is {{convert|42|km|0|abbr=on}} long. Along it there are small beaches, including an artificial one. Gore Chirakman with its almost sheer slopes towers above the seacoast. Remains of stronghold walls, moats, buildings, churches and [[necropolis]]es can be found on the flat [[plateau]]. The region is rich in mineral waters.\n\nThe area around Kavarna offers opportunities for developing ecotourism and specialized tourism&nbsp;\u2014 examination and photography of plants, dolphins and various kinds of fish in the coastal waters. The variety of birds attracts tourists from all parts of the world and contributes to Kaliakra and Yaylata becoming one of the most preferred places in Bulgaria for the development of ornithological tourism.\n\n==Population==\n\n<!--THIS TABLE IS STANDARD TO ALL BULGARIAN CITIES ARTICLES. PLEASE LEAVE -->\n{{Table BG town population\n| city = Kavarna\n| 1887 = no data\n| 1910 = no data\n| 1934 = no data\n| 1946 = 5,652\n| 1956 = 7,053\n| 1965 = 8,300\n| 1975 = 10,881\n| 1985 = 12,033\n| 1992 = 12,139\n| 2001 = 11,479\n| 2005 = 11,415\n| 2007 = 11,438\n| 2009 = 11,397\n| ref 1 = <ref name=\"statistika\"/>\n| ref 2 = <ref name=\"population\"/>\n| ref 3 = <ref name=\"pop-stat\"/>\n| ref 4 = <ref name=\"BAN\">{{in lang|bg}} [http://www.geography.iit.bas.bg/2009/1-09/13-17.pdf Bulgarian Academy of Sciences] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706142758/http://www.geography.iit.bas.bg/2009/1-09/13-17.pdf |date=2011-07-06 }}</ref></small>\n}}\n\n==History==\n[[File:Karvuna 1.jpg|left|thumb|250px|[[Kaliakra]]]]\n\nThe town was founded in the 5th century BC by [[Ancient Greece|Ancient Greek]]<ref>An Inventory of Archaic and Classical Poleis: An Investigation Conducted by The Copenhagen Polis Centre for the Danish National Research Foundation by Mogens Herman Hansen,2005,Index</ref> colonists who settled on the [[Chirakman Plateau]] in the colony '''Byzone''' (or ''Bizone'') ({{lang-grc|\u0392\u03b9\u03b6\u03ce\u03bd\u03b7}}). During the 3rd and 2nd century BC, the town played an important mediating role between the local [[Thracians|Thracian]] settlements and the Greeks. Despite being unsuitable for wharfing because of its rugged cliffs, this part of the [[Bulgarian Black Sea Coast]] was an attractive centre due to the fact that the local people produced and traded with high quality grain.\n\nDuring the second part of the 1st century BC the ancient town fell in the sea because of a disastrous earthquake. The frontal part of the Chirakman broke off and together with the richest citizens fell into the [[Black Sea]]'s waters. According to the leader of the finished first part of the underwater archaeological expedition Kavarna 2005, Asen Salkin, the Roman town of Bizone has sunk two times in the sea. For that evidence the located form skin-divers borders of a sunk residential district of the town of Bizone in Kavarna's coast. For the presence of residential buildings the archaeologists judge by the found ashlars and parts of brick walls. The finds date from the 2nd century AD. According to the leader of the expedition this residential district has nothing in common with the disastrous earthquake from the 1st century BC. The underwater finds evidence for other phenomenon, for which the scientists express only suppositions, such as transgression and regression of the strata. It has started to transgress during the 1st century AD and this has continued to the 2nd century. It is possible that during this period the coast had risen by four metres and one day it suddenly fallen through.\n\nDuring [[Ancient Rome|Roman times]] the town was restored under the same name and quickly flourished, the settlement revived and the port brightened up.\n\n[[File:Kavarna HDR.jpg|thumb|300px|View of Kavarna]]\nIn the 7th century AD the [[Slavs]] and [[Asparuh]]'s [[Bulgars]] destroyed the [[Byzantine]] town and later founded a new settlement, which entered the [[First Bulgarian Empire]]. In the late Middle Ages the settlement grew and was subject to [[Tatar]] raids; in the 14th century it became part of the [[Principality of Karvuna]], which de facto broke away from the Second Bulgarian Empire under the rule of the [[Despot (court title)|despot]]s [[Balik (Bulgarian ruler)|Balik]] and [[Dobrotitsa]] of the Bulgarian royal Terter dynasty.<ref>\u0413. \u0411\u0430\u043a\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0432, ''\u0418\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u044f \u043d\u0430 \u0431\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u0442\u0435'', \u0422\u043e\u043c 1, 2003, \u0441. 457</ref><ref>\u041f\u0435\u0442\u044a\u0440 \u041d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0432, ''\u0421\u043a\u0432\u0438\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u043a\u043d\u044f\u0437\u0435 \u041f\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0446\u0438-\u0420\u043e\u0436\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438&nbsp;\u2014 \u043a\u043b\u043e\u043d \u043d\u0430 \u0434\u0438\u043d\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438\u044f\u0442\u0430 \u0422\u0435\u0440\u0442\u0435\u0440'', online, retrieved 03-24-2007</ref>  In 1397, the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman Turks]] nearly destroyed the city, which was abandoned but resettled again and rebuilt by the early 17th century. Its present name was documented for the first time in the early 15th century.\n\nThe town was considered an economical and cultural centre during [[ancient history|Antiquity]] and the [[Middle Ages]] with rich and various remains&nbsp;\u2013 stronghold walls, early-[[Christianity|Christian]] [[basilica]], [[medieval]] [[church (building)|church]]es, and public buildings.\n\nNotable works of art, such as coins from different historical epochs, golden adornments, a golden Thracian treasure of applications, have been found in the area. Between the 15th and 19th century the town becomes popular under the name Kavarna, as a Christian settlement and port for grain export. From that time remain a Turkish bath, a medieval necropolis, a bridge, fountains, Christian churches and many inscriptions.\n\nDuring the [[Russo-Turkish War of 1877\u20131878]] Kavarna's Christian inhabitants, Bulgarians and [[Gagauz people|Gagauz]] alike, rebelled against the [[bashi-bazouk]]s and Circassian hordes. After the liberation the town became part of the [[Principality of Bulgaria]].\n\nFrom the beginning of 20th century Kavarna achieved a rapid progress as an economical and cultural centre. The town renamed ''Cavarna'' came under [[Romania]]n rule after the [[Second Balkan War]] in 1913 and again after the [[First World War]] in 1919.  This however, was met with resistance by the local Bulgarian population and its [[Internal Dobrujan Revolutionary Organisation]]. In 1940 the town was ceded back to Bulgaria by the [[Treaty of Craiova]].\n\n==Monuments and museums==\n\n===Dobruja and the Sea Display===\nThe Dobruja and the Sea Display is a small maritime museum. It is situated in an approximately restored [[Turkey|Turkish]] bath, the Hamam. It was built in the beginning of the 15th century and represents a massive beehive bath from stone, situated in the beginning of the valley leading to the port, and half a kilometre apart from the town centre. Many stone anchors, amphorae and ceramics found during the underwater archaeological expeditions are exposed there. Coins from different epochs and a golden Thracian treasure can be seen in the Treasure House Hall  The ancient and mediaeval colour painting expend our concepts for the ancient navigation around Dobruja's coasts.\n\n===Town Museum===\nThe Town Museum can be found in the building of the local library. Materials, revealing the thousand-year old history of the town are displayed in its exposition. Evidence for the life of the people in the region since ancient times are represented here. A model of prehistoric cave-dwellings, many tools, guns, rifles and pistols from the War of Liberation, as well as ethnographic materials&nbsp;\u2014 clothing, finery, folk-style cloth, are also exhibited\n\n===Ethnographic Museum===\n[[File:Dormition of the Theotokos Church - Kavarna.jpg|right|thumb|250px|Dormition of the Theotokos Church.]]\n\nThe Ethnographic Museum represents an old house from the end of the 19th century that belonged to a rich family. Its interior reveals the customs and culture of the people inhabiting that part of the country; premises typical for Dobruja houses, tools from the culture and the daily round of the people. The building is surrounded by a garden full of mulberry trees, peonies and tulips.\n\n===Churches===\nThere are two churches in the town both located in the town centre. The Church of [[Saint George]] was built in 1836 and the Dormition of the Theotokos Church in 1860. Both churches played an important role during the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] rule and after the Liberation as educational and cultural centers.\n\n===The old fountains===\nThese were 12 spring fountains situated along the valley to the port. Some of them were destroyed and the rest were restored recently. The great amount of spring water forms a small river.\n\n==Culture==\nSince 2004 the town has turned in one of the centres of musical life in Bulgaria. Kavarna has been the host to several [[Rock (music)|rock and roll]] concerts. In 2005 the most popular band to play in the town's stadium was [[Deep Purple]]. The other notable performers were mostly legends of German rock and [[heavy metal music]], such as [[Scorpions (band)|Scorpions]], [[Axel Rudi Pell]], [[Gamma Ray (band)|Gamma Ray]], [[Masterplan (band)|Masterplan]] and [[Destruction (band)|Destruction]]. On 27 August 2005 [[Accept (band)|Accept]], another German band, played here its last show with original lead vocalist [[Udo Dirkschneider]]. There is also a mural of [[Whitesnake]] singer [[David Coverdale]].\n\n2006 saw the start of the [[Kaliakra Rock Fest]] - A Metal festival (renamed to [[Kaliakra Rock Fest|Kavarna Rock Fest]] in 2010) including many metal bands. The same year followed the tradition with concerts of more metal bands as well as some pop and dance musicians. For example, Russian pop star [[Filipp Kirkorov]] sang there in September.\n\nIn 2007, performers included [[Heaven and Hell (band)|Heaven and Hell]], [[John Lawton (musician)|John Lawton]] Band, [[Manowar]], [[Mot\u00f6rhead]], [[Robert Plant]], and [[Ronnie James Dio]]. The next year saw the return of Manowar within [[Kaliakra Rock Fest]] with a 5-hour attempt to set a world record for the longest heavy metal concert. The next two days [[Alice Cooper]], [[Slayer]] and [[In Flames]] held concerts. In July 2009, [[M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce]] headlined the rock-fest, with Scorpions, [[Blind Guardian]] and [[Dream Theater]] also participating. [[Sonata Arctica]] also performed in 2008 and 2011.\n\nThe 2013 [[Volvo World Match Play Championship]] was held at the [[Thracian Cliffs Golf Course]].\n\n==International relations==\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in Poland}}\n\n===Twin towns and sister cities===\nKavarna is [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with:\n\n*{{flagicon|RUS}} [[Podolsk]], Russia<ref name=\"Podolsk twinnings\">{{cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?sourceid=navclient&hl=en&u=http%3a%2f%2fadmpodolsk.ru%2findex.php%3fcategoryid%3d126|title=Podolsk sister cities|publisher=Translate.google.com|date=|accessdate=2010-04-29}}</ref>\n\n===Honour===\n[[Kavarna Cove]] in [[Livingston Island]] in the [[South Shetland Islands]], [[Antarctica]] is named after Kavarna.\n\n==Gallery==\n{{center|<gallery>\nFile:Kavarna Bulgaria architecture.jpg|Architecture of Kavarna\nFile:Kavarna-church-mihalorel.JPG|Church in Kavarna\nFile:Dio monument.jpeg|[[Ronnie James Dio]] statue\nFile:David Coverdale Kavarna mural.png|[[David Coverdale]] mural\n</gallery>}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://www.kavarna.bg/ Official homepage]\n* [http://www.guide-bulgaria.com/NE/Dobrich/Kavarna Guide to Kavarna municipality]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070717223959/http://www.kavarnamap.eu/index_en.php Interactive map of Kavarna]\n\n{{Dobrich Province}}\n{{Bulgarian Black Sea resorts}}\n{{Kavarna}}\n{{Cities in Bulgaria}}\n\n[[Category:Towns in Bulgaria]]\n[[Category:Seaside resorts in Bulgaria]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Dobrich Province]]\n[[Category:Populated coastal places in Bulgaria]]\n[[Category:Greek colonies on the Black Sea coast]]\n", "name_user": "WOSlinker", "label": "safe", "comment": "fix small tags", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kavarna"}
{"title_page": "The Altar Stairs", "text_new": "{{short description|1922 film}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Altar Stairs\n| image          = Frank Mayo-Louise Lorraine in The Altar Stairs.jpg\n| caption        = Film still with Frank Mayo and Louise Lorraine\n| director       = [[Lambert Hillyer]]\n| producer       = \n| writer         = [[George Hively]]<br>[[Doris Schroeder]]\n| based on       = {{basedon|''The Altar Stairs''|[[G. B. Lancaster]]}}\n| starring       = [[Frank Mayo (actor)|Frank Mayo]]<br>[[Louise Lorraine]]\n| cinematography = Dwight Warren\n| editing        = \n| distributor    = [[Universal Studios|Universal Pictures]]\n| released       = {{film date|1922|12|04}}\n| runtime        = 5 [[reel#Motion picture terminology|reels]]\n| country        = United States \n| language       = Silent (English [[intertitle]]s)\n}}\n\n'''''The Altar Stairs''''' is a 1922 American [[silent film|silent]] [[drama film]] directed by [[Lambert Hillyer]] and featuring [[Boris Karloff]].<ref name=\"silentera\">{{cite web |url=http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/A/AltarStairs1922.html |title=Progressive Silent Film List: The Altar Stairs |accessdate=April 7, 2008|work=silentera.com}}</ref> It is based on the novel of the same name by [[G. B. Lancaster]]. It is not known whether the film currently survives,<ref name=\"silentera\"/> suggesting that it is a [[lost film]].<ref>[http://memory.loc.gov/diglib/ihas/loc.mbrs.sfdb.3395/default.html  The Library of Congress/FIAF American Silent Feature Film Survival Catalog: ''The Altar Stairs'']</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nRod McLean (Mayo), a [[South Seas (genre)|South Seas]] trader, saves derelict Tony Heritage (Hughes) from some natives, and Tony repays him by stealing his money and escaping to France. There he marries Joie (Lorraine), the daughter of Captain Jean Malet (Lanoe) who is soon to take a post in the South Seas. When the officer learns of Tony's record, he repudiates the marriage and takes Joie with him to the South Seas. Tony then turns up there, and Captain Malet, to keep him away from Joie, gives him a job helping Rod establish a new trading post on another island. Rod has fallen in love with Joie, but after he discovers that she is married (although he does not know to whom), he rejects her as a flirt. \n\nBack at the new post, Rod discovers that Tony has gotten the natives drunk and they are burning the island chapel. He finds out that Tony is Joie's husband, but is stopped by the minister from killing him. Tony uses Rod's boat to escape to a steamer. Rod goes after him, followed by the minister who wants to prevent any killing, while Joie awaits the film's climax on the main island.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Illustrated Screen Report: ''The Altar Stairs'' |journal=Exhibitor's Trade Review |volume=13 |issue=3 |page=155 |publisher=Exhibitor's Trade Review, Inc. |location=East Stroudsberg, Pennsylvania |date=December 16, 1922 |url=https://archive.org/details/exhibitorst00newy |accessdate=April 24, 2014}}</ref> \n\n==Cast==\n* [[Frank Mayo (actor)|Frank Mayo]] as Rod McLean\n* [[Louise Lorraine]] as Joie Malet\n* Lawrence Hughes as Tony Heritage\n* J. Jiquel Lanoe as Captain Jean Malet (credited as J.J. Lanoe)\n* [[Harry De Vere]] as Blundell\n* [[Hugh Thompson (American actor)|Hugh Thompson]] as John Strickland\n* [[Boris Karloff]] as Hugo\n* [[Dagmar Godowsky]] as Parete\n* [[Nick De Ruiz]] as Tulli\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of American films of 1922]]\n* [[Boris Karloff filmography]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|The Altar Stairs}}\n*{{IMDb title|0012891}}\n*{{allmovie|83557|synopsis}}\n*[http://www.southseascinema.org SouthSeasCinema]; a webpage devoted to Pacific Island themed films\n\n{{Lambert Hillyer}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Altar Stairs, The}}\n[[Category:1922 films]]\n[[Category:1920s drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American drama films]]\n[[Category:American silent feature films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Lambert Hillyer]]\n[[Category:Universal Pictures films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1922 film}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Altar Stairs\n| image          = Frank Mayo-Louise Lorraine in The Altar Stairs.jpg\n| caption        = Film still with Frank Mayo and Louise Lorraine\n| director       = [[Lambert Hillyer]]\n| producer       = \n| writer         = [[George Hively]]<br>[[Doris Schroeder]]\n| based on       = {{basedon|''The Altar Stairs''|[[G. B. Lancaster]]}}\n| starring       = [[Frank Mayo (actor)|Frank Mayo]]<br>[[Louise Lorraine]]\n| cinematography = Dwight Warren\n| editing        = \n| distributor    = [[Universal Studios|Universal Pictures]]\n| released       = {{film date|1922|12|04}}\n| runtime        = 5 [[reel#Motion picture terminology|reels]]\n| country        = United States \n| language       = Silent (English [[intertitle]]s)\n}}\n\n'''''The Altar Stairs''''' is a 1922 American [[silent film|silent]] [[drama film]] directed by [[Lambert Hillyer]] and featuring [[Boris Karloff]].<ref name=\"silentera\">{{cite web |url=http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/A/AltarStairs1922.html |title=Progressive Silent Film List: The Altar Stairs |accessdate=April 7, 2008|work=silentera.com}}</ref> It is based on the novel of the same name by [[G. B. Lancaster]]. It is not known whether the film currently survives,<ref name=\"silentera\"/> suggesting that it is a [[lost film]].<ref>[http://memory.loc.gov/diglib/ihas/loc.mbrs.sfdb.3395/default.html  The Library of Congress/FIAF American Silent Feature Film Survival Catalog: ''The Altar Stairs'']</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nRod McLean (Mayo), a [[South Seas (genre)|South Seas]] trader, saves derelict Tony Heritage (Hughes) from some natives, and Tony repays him by stealing his money and escaping to France. There he marries Joie (Lorraine), the daughter of Captain Jean Malet (Lanoe) who is soon to take a post in the South Seas. When the officer learns of Tony's record, he repudiates the marriage and takes Joie with him to the South Seas. Tony then turns up there, and Captain Malet, to keep him away from Joie, gives him a job helping Rod establish a new trading post on another island. Rod has fallen in love with Joie, but after he discovers that she is married (although he does not know to whom), he rejects her as a flirt. \n\nBack at the new post, Rod discovers that Tony has gotten the natives drunk and they are burning the island chapel. He finds out that Tony is Joie's husband, but is stopped by the minister from killing him. Tony uses Rod's boat to escape to a steamer. Rod goes after him, followed by the minister who wants to prevent any killing, while Joie awaits the film's climax on the main island.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Illustrated Screen Report: ''The Altar Stairs'' |journal=Exhibitor's Trade Review |volume=13 |issue=3 |page=155 |publisher=Exhibitor's Trade Review, Inc. |location=East Stroudsberg, Pennsylvania |date=December 16, 1922 |url=https://archive.org/details/exhibitorst00newy |accessdate=April 24, 2014}}</ref> \n\n==Cast==\n* [[Frank Mayo (actor)|Frank Mayo]] as Rod McLean\n* [[Louise Lorraine]] as Joie Malet\n* Lawrence Hughes as Tony Heritage\n* J. Jiquel Lanoe as Captain Jean Malet (credited as J.J. Lanoe)\n* [[Harry De Vere]] as Blundell\n* [[Hugh Thompson (American actor)|Hugh Thompson]] as John Strickland\n* [[Boris Karloff]] as Hugo\n* [[Dagmar Godowsky]] as Parete\n* [[Nick De Ruiz]] as Tulli\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of American films of 1922]]\n* [[Boris Karloff filmography]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|The Altar Stairs}}\n*{{IMDb title|0012891}}\n*{{allmovie|83557|synopsis}}\n*[http://www.southseascinema.org SouthSeasCinema]; a webpage devoted to Pacific Island themed films\n\n{{Lambert Hillyer}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Altar Stairs, The}}\n[[Category:1922 films]]\n[[Category:1920s drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American drama films]]\n[[Category:American silent feature films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Lambert Hillyer]]\n[[Category:Universal Pictures films]]\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Altar_Stairs"}
{"title_page": "Rodulf (petty king)", "text_new": "{{other uses|Rodulf (disambiguation)}}\n'''King Rodulf''' is described by both [[Procopius]] and [[Paul the Deacon]] as the king of the [[Heruli]] kingdom on the [[Middle Danube]], who died when they were defeated by the [[Lombards]], some time between 494 and 508. After this defeat, in 512, Procopius reported that some of the Heruli nobility migrated north to [[Thule]] (what he called [[Scandinavia]]), settling near the ''Dani'' ([[Danes]]).\n\nIt is uncertain whether this Rodulf is the same king described in the ''[[Getica]]'' of [[Jordanes]] as the king of the [[Ranii]] on the island of [[Scandza]] (what he called Scandinavia), who left his kingdom near the Danes, and came to Italy, where he was embraced by the [[Ostrogoths|Ostrogothic]] [[King of Italy]], [[Theodoric the Great]]. Notably, Jordanes also mentions that the Heruli had been living in this area also, until they were driven out by the Danes, but he does not connect this Rodulf to these Heruli.\n\nThe Scandza passage of Jordanes is subject to many different interpretations, and some historians have proposed that Jordanes made errors. For example, [[Theodor Mommsen]] believed Jordanes should have described the Scandinavian Rudolf as a Herul, and the historian [[Herwig Wolfram]] has described this Scandinavian Rudolf as a [[Gaut]].<ref name=\"Wolfram2004p19\">Wolfram (2004) p. 49</ref>\n\nDue to the similarity of the circumstances, it has been suggested that the various accounts describe one individual, although this remains uncertain. Apart from the name Rudolf, the association with the region of the Dani, their apparent allegiance to Theoderic is notable. In a passage mentioning the Heruli, Jordanes mentioned that Theoderic adopted their king (who is not named in that passage) as a \"son in arms\". It is thus possible that Theoderic helped established him as king of the Heruli.\n\nMore speculatively, another debated issue is whether Rodulf could be the background for certain aspects of later heroic poetry, possibly including the [[Norsemen|Norse]] [[saga]] character [[Hr\u00f3lfr Kraki]].\n\n==King in Scandza==\n[[File:Jordanes, Norway tribes.png|thumb|340px|Locations of the tribes described by Jordanes in Norway, contemporary with, and some possibly ruled by Rodulf.]]\nKing Rodulf (''Roduulf rex'')<ref name=\"Maenchen\"/> of the Ranii tribe appears in the ''[[Getica]]'' (''De origine actibusque Getarum''; \"The Origin and Deeds of the Goths\") of the Roman historian [[Jordanes]]. Building on the now lost ''Historia Gothorum'' (\"History of the Goths\") of [[Cassiodorus]], Jordanes wrote his account at the request of [[Theodoric the Great]], King of the [[Ostrogoths]] and [[King of Italy|ruler of Italy]].<ref>Helle (2003) p. 82</ref> In the ''Getica'', it is said that Rodulf spurned his own kingdom,<ref name=\"Maenchen\">Maenchen-Helfen (1973) p. 487</ref> namely that of the \"Ranii\" tribe from Ragnaricii - Ranrike/Ranerike in today's Western Sweden. He therefore fled, likely together with a band of warriors,<ref>Skre (2008) p. 288</ref> to seek the sanctuary and support of Theodoric in [[Ravenna]] around 500.<ref name=\"Wolfram2004p19\"/>\n\nIt is unclear whether he was king of the Ranii tribe alone, or if he ruled all, or any other<ref name=\"Skre257\">Skre (2008) p. 257</ref> of the tribes described in the same context (as being the neighbours to the [[Heruli]], who were driven from their homes), namely the \"Granii, Augandzi, Eunixi, Taetel, Rugii, Aprochi.\"<ref name=\"Maenchen\"/> This list has been transliterated to mean the \"Grannii, A[u]gandzi, Eunixi <e>t Aetelrugi, Arothi,\"<ref>Nordgren (2004) p. 387</ref> and the tribes described identified as the inhabitants of [[Grenland]] (Grannii), [[Agder]] (A[u]gand''zi''), the \"island inhabitants\"<ref name=\"Nordgren\">Nordgren (2004) p. 464</ref> possibly of [[Karm\u00f8y]]<ref name=\"Thurston\">Thurston (1996) p. 111</ref> (Eunixi), the \"head [[Rugii]]\" of [[Rogaland]] (Aetelrugi) and [[Charudes|the inhabitants]] of [[Hordaland]] (Arothi).<ref name=\"Nordgren\"/> The vast geographic distances between the tribes, scattered throughout the Norwegian coast,<ref name=\"Skre257\"/> and the unlikeliness of a unified kingdom of such a magnitude at this early point<ref>Koht (1955) p. 12</ref> has been cited as arguments against such a possibility.\n\nSince the tribes are listed only in the context of being neighbours to the Heruli in the latter's former homeland, historian [[Otto J. Maenchen-Helfen]] thought it to be a linguistic error to interpret Rodulf as king of the tribes mentioned, instead holding that Rodulf should actually be read as king of the Heruli, as part of the greater context.<ref name=\"Maenchen\"/> Assuming that Rodulf had ruled all the tribes mentioned, historian Axel Kristinsson has speculated that it could have been natural for Rodulf to seek out some of his kinsmen, namely the southern Rugians who had joined the Ostrogoths as the Rogii sub-tribe after their kingdom was destroyed in 487.<ref>Kristinsson (2010) p. 225</ref> Historian A. H. Merrills, on the other hand, has proposed the possibility that placing Rodulf's origin with the Scandinavian tribes could have been politically motivated. Since Theodoric sought to expand his connections in the north at the time, his support of a northern exile would have given him significant benefits.<ref>Merrills (2005) p. 129</ref>\n\nSome modern historians have speculated that it could have been Rodulf, or potentially some of his subjects, who provided Cassiodorus or Jordanes with the information for their extensive lists and details of [[Scandinavia]]n peoples and tribes.<ref>Christensen (2002) pp. 270\u2013271, Fouracre (2005) p. 501, Skre (1998) p. 256, Goffart (2009) p. 64 and Merrills (2005) pp. 128\u2013129</ref> In any case, Rodulf was not the only Nordic warlord who visited the Goths and potentially could have provided knowledge about Scandinavian tribes.<ref>Skre (1998) pp. 256\u2013257</ref>\n\n==King of the Heruls==\nThe Byzantine scholar [[Procopius]] relates that the Heruli tribe had a king<ref name=\"ReallexikonKrag\"/> or leader (''h\u00e9gemon'')<ref>Weibull (1987) p. 8</ref> called Rodulf (''Rhodoulphos'') during the reign of the Byzantine emperor [[Anastasius I (emperor)|Anastasius]].<ref name=\"ReallexikonKrag\">Krag (2003) p. 58</ref> In the ''[[History of the Lombards|Historia Langobardorum]]'' (\"History of the Lombards\"), [[Paul the Deacon]] mentions that Rodulf was among the dead in a battle against the [[Lombards]]<ref name=\"ReallexikonKrag\"/> under [[Tato]], probably in 508.<ref name=\"ReallexikonWolfram\"/><ref name=\"Wolfram\"/> According to Procopius, Rodulf was enticed by his people to declare war against the Lombards, despite the latter's attempt of maintaining peace.<ref>Goffart (2009) pp. 207\u2013208</ref> A later version by Paul the Deacon gives Rodulf a legitimate ''[[casus belli]]'',<ref>Goffart (2009) p. 208</ref> as Rodulf purportedly declared war against the Lombards because his brother was murdered by Tato's daughter Rumetruda, after a fall-out between the two during his brother's return home after he had concluded peace with the Lombards.<ref name=\"Paul1XX\">Paul the Deacon, [http://www.northvegr.org/histories%20and%20chronicles/history%20of%20the%20lombards/005.html 1. XX]</ref> Theodoric did not manage to intervene in time, and the Heruls thus suffered a crushing defeat.<ref name=\"Wolfram\"/> The Heruls were split up as a result of the defeat in the battle.<ref name=\"ReallexikonKrag\"/> As Rodulf lost both his standard (''vexillum'') and his helmet, both considered irreplaceable in Germanic thought, he was the last true king of the Heruls.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Journal of Roman Studies|publisher=Kraus Reprint|year=1968|volume=40-42|page=204|url=https://books.google.com/books?ei=uinnUIDCG6bl4QS7woGYBQ&hl=no&id=zys8AAAAMAAJ&dq=rodulf+germanic+herul&q=%22because+in+Germanic+thought%22#search_anchor}}</ref>\n[[File:Theoderic Quarter Siliqua 80000847.jpg|thumb|210px|Coin of Theodoric the Great.]]\n\nJordanes also tells of an unnamed king of the Heruli, who has been identified with Rodulf by some historians.<ref name=\"ReallexikonKrag\"/> He writes that Theodoric adopted a king of the Heruli as his \"son in arms,\" by giving him a horse, sword and shield (possibly around 507)<ref name=\"ReallexikonWolfram\">Wolfram (2006) p. 50</ref> similarly to what his father [[Theodemir (Ostrogothic king)|Theodemir]] formerly had done with the [[Suebi]] chieftain [[Hunimund]].<ref name=\"Wolfram\"/> The accompanying letter to the king, which was translated into \"German,\" read that the king would \"hold the first rank among the peoples.\"<ref name=\"ReallexikonWolfram\"/><ref name=\"Wolfram\"/> In a letter referred to by Cassiodorus, probably from between 507 and 514, Theodoric asks for the assistance of the kings of the Heruli, [[Thuringii|Thuringi]] and [[Warini|Varni]] tribes for a counter-attack against the pressure from the [[Franks]].<ref name=\"ReallexikonKrag\"/> Although Procopius claims the battle took place in 494, the battle, which led to Rodulf's death, is therefore considered unlikely to have occurred before 508.<ref name=\"ReallexikonKrag\"/>\n\nThe Heruls are considered to have been an originally Scandinavian people.<ref name=\"ReallexikonKrag\"/> After migrating southwards, the group later settled at the river [[Morava (river)|Morava]] following the Ostrogothic departure from [[Pannonian Basin|Pannonia]] in 473, and established a federated kingdom that extended across the Danube and into the Roman Empire. After becoming ruler of Italy, Theodoric travelled to what was described as the previous homeland of the [[Goths]], and thereafter, according to historian [[Herwig Wolfram]], wanted to establish an alliance with the Heruli king Rodulf. According to Wolfram, Rodulf \"probably included in his sphere of influence the region north of [[Lake Balaton]].\"<ref name=\"Wolfram\">Wolfram (1990) p. 318</ref>\n\n==Identifying Rodulf==\nThe German [[Classics|classicist]] [[Theodor Mommsen]] argued that the Rodulf of the Ranii tribe and the Rodulf of the Heruli tribe constituted the same person. He proposed that Rodulf could have arrived to Theodoric in 489, when he was in [[Moesia]].<ref name=\"Skre257\"/> Similarly, the scientist-explorer [[Fridtjof Nansen]] proposed that \"Heruli\" at first perhaps was a common name for bands of northern warriors, who to a certain degree consisted of Norwegians. In his book ''In northern mists'', Nansen suggested that Rodulf of the Ranii tribe could have migrated south with a band of warriors, and that on arriving at the [[Danube]], pressed by other warlike tribes in the vicinity, he sought alliance with Theodoric. Nansen believed this could have happened before Theodoric's invasion of [[Italy]] in 489, at the same time that the Heruli were just north of the Danube, and were the nearest neighbours of the Goths.<ref name=\"Nansen\">Nansen (1911) pp. 137\u2013139</ref>\n\nAlthough particularly German scholarship have identified the unnamed Heruli king and the Rodulfs as the same person,<ref name=\"Goffart3356\">Goffart (2009) pp. 335\u2013336</ref> including the ''[[Reallexikon der Germanischen Altertumskunde]]'' in an entry by Norwegian historian [[Claus Krag]],<ref name=\"ReallexikonKrag\"/> others such as historian [[Walter Goffart]] and archaeologist Dagfinn Skre have questioned at least parts of these identifications.<ref>Skre (1998) p. 257 and Goffart (2009) pp. 335\u2013336</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nIn the early 6th century, the Lombard king [[Wacho]] took [[Silinga of the Heruli|Silinga]] as his third wife, who was said to be the daughter of the last king of the Heruls.<ref>Waldman and Mason (2006) p. 389</ref> This has led some scholars to believe that Silinga probably was a daughter of Rodulf;<ref>{{Cite book|title=[[Reallexikon der Germanischen Altertumskunde]]|editor1=Beck, Heinrich |editor2=Geuenich, Dieter |editor3=Steuer, Heiko |publisher=Walter de Gruyter|year=2006|language=German|volume=33|isbn=978-3-11-018388-7|page=6}}</ref> she again had the son [[Walthari]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Zeitschrift f\u00fcr die Geschichte des Oberrheins|url=https://books.google.com/books?ei=mjbnUMLPDoiN4ATvo4C4Cw&hl=no&id=pxtoAAAAMAAJ&dq=%22silinga%22+rodulf&q=%22sohnes+walthari%22#search_anchor|volume=149|publisher=G. Braun.|year=2001|page=36|language=German}}</ref> The marriage between Wacho and Silinga functioned to legitimize the Lombards as the successors to the kingdom of the Heruls.<ref>Wolfram (1995) p. 21</ref>\n\nIt has been debated whether Rodulf may have influenced later heroic poetry, since the causes of the war between the Lombards and the Heruli (as reported by Paul the Deacon) concerns related issues. Some have furthermore argued that Rodulf could be the background for the character [[Hr\u00f3lfr Kraki]] who appears in the later [[saga]]s. Evidence for this includes the significant similarities between the traditions of, on the one side, the [[Scylding]]s of the ''[[Skj\u00f6ldunga saga]]'' and the [[Yngling|Scylfings]] of the Swedish sagas, and on the other, historical knowledge of the environment around the Heruli, Goths and [[Hun]]s.<ref>Krag (2003) pp. 58\u201359</ref>\n\nIt has also been speculated that the R\u00e1\u00f0ulfr mentioned in the [[R\u00f6k Runestone]] (which also mentions Theodoric the Great) could be identical with Rodulf.<ref name=\"Nansen\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n===Primary sources===\n* [[Cassiodorus]], ''The Letters of Cassiodorus'', [http://www.gutenberg.org/files/18590/18590-h/18590-h.htm#Page_236 IV. 2.], [http://www.gutenberg.org/files/18590/18590-h/18590-h.htm#Page_198 III. 3.]\n* [[Jordanes]], ''The Origin and Deeds of the Goths'', [http://www.romansonline.com/Src_Frame.asp?DocID=Gth_Goth_03 3. 24.]\n* [[Paul the Deacon]], ''History of the Lombards'', [http://www.northvegr.org/histories%20and%20chronicles/history%20of%20the%20lombards/005.html I. XX.]\n* [[Procopius]], ''The Wars of Justinian'', [http://www.gutenberg.org/files/20298/20298-h/20298-h.htm#VI_xiv_11 VI. xiv.]\n\n===Modern sources===\n* {{Cite book|title=The New Cambridge Medieval History: Volume 1, c.500-c.700|author=Fouracre, Paul|publisher=Cambridge University|year=2005|isbn=978-0-521-36291-7|page=501}}\n* {{Cite book|title=Barbarian Tides: The Migration Age and the Later Roman Empire|author=[[Walter Goffart|Goffart, Walter]]|publisher=University of Pennsylvania|year=2009|isbn=978-0-8122-2105-3}}\n* {{Cite book|title=The Cambridge History of Scandinavia|volume=1|author=[[Knut Helle|Helle, Knut]]|publisher=Cambridge University|year=2003|isbn=978-0-521-47299-9|page=82}}\n* {{Cite book|title= Harald H\u00e5rfagre og rikssamlinga |author=[[Halvdan Koht|Koht, Halvdan]]|publisher=Aschehoug|year=1955|language=Norwegian|page=12}}\n* {{Cite book|title=[[Reallexikon der Germanischen Altertumskunde]]|author=[[Claus Krag|Krag, Claus]]|publisher=Walter de Gruyter|volume=25|year=2003|language=German|chapter=Rodulf|editor=Beck, Heinrich |editor2=Geuenich, Dieter |editor3=Steuer, Heiko|isbn=3-11-017733-1|pages=58\u201359}}\n* {{Cite book|title=Expansions: Competition and Conquest in Europe since the Bronze Age|author=Kristinsson, Axel|publisher=Reykjav\u00edkurAkadem\u00edan|year=2010|isbn=978-9979-9922-1-9}}\n* {{Cite book|title=The World of the Huns: Studies in Their History and Culture|author=Maenchen-Helfen, Otto|publisher=University of California|year=1973|isbn=978-0-520-01596-8|page=487}}\n* {{Cite book|title=Nordwestgermanisch|author1=Marold, Edith  |author2=Zimmermann, Christiane |lastauthoramp=yes |publisher=Walter de Gruyter|year=1995|language=German|isbn=978-3-11-014818-3|page=78}}\n* {{Cite book|title=History and Geography in Late Antiquity|author=Merrills, A. H.|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2005|isbn=978-0-521-84601-1}}\n* {{Cite book|title=In northern mists; Arctic exploration in early times|volume=1|author=[[Fridtjof Nansen|Nansen, Fridtjof]]|publisher=Library of Alexandria|year=1911|isbn=978-1-4655-4901-3|pages=137\u2013139}}\n* {{Cite book|title=The Well Spring Of The Goths: About The Gothic Peoples In The Nordic Countries And On The Continent|author=Nordgren, Ingemar|publisher=iUniverse|year=2004|isbn=978-0-595-33648-7|pages=464}}\n* {{Cite book|title=Herred\u00f8mmet: bosetning og besittelse p\u00e5 Romerike 200-1350 e. Kr|author=Skre, Dagfinn|year=1998|publisher=Universitetsforlaget|location=University of Oslo|language=Norwegian|isbn=82-00-12854-7}}\n* {{Cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_qzVAAAAMAAJ&q=ranii+raumi&dq=ranii+raumi&hl=no&sa=X&ei=QDf7UMPFCYf34QT614GIBw&redir_esc=y|title=The development and transformation of a prehistoric cultural landscape: boundaries, integration, and political economy in the south Scandinavian Iron Age|volume=1|author=Thurston, Tina L.|publisher=University of Wisconsin--Madison|year=1996|page=111}}\n* {{Cite book|author1=Waldman, Carl  |author2=Mason, Catherine |lastauthoramp=yes |year=2006|title=Encyclopedia of European Peoples|publisher=Infobase Publishing|isbn=978-1-4381-2918-1}}\n* {{Cite book|title=Scandia|volume=53|author=Weibull, Lauritz Ulrik Absalon|year=1987|publisher=Statens humanistiska forskningsr\u00e5d}}\n* {{Cite book|title=History of the Goths|author=[[Herwig Wolfram|Wolfram, Herwig]]|publisher=University of California|year=1990|origyear=First published in Germany in 1979|language=German|isbn=0-520-06983-8|page=318}}\n* {{Cite book|title=Salzburg, Bayern, \u00d6sterreich: Conversio Bagoariorum et Carantanorum und die Quellen ihrer Zeit|author=Wolfram, Herwig|publisher=Oldenbourg Verlag|year=1995|language=German|isbn=978-3-7029-0404-3}}\n* {{Cite book|title=Early Germanic Literature and Culture|editor=Murdoch, Brian |editor2=Read, Malcolm Kevin|author=Wolfram, Herwig|publisher=Boydell & Brewer|year=2004|chapter=Origo Gentis: The Literature of Germanic Origins|isbn=1-57113-199-X|pages=39\u201354}}\n* {{Cite book|title=[[Reallexikon der Germanischen Altertumskunde]]|editor1=Beck, Heinrich |editor2=Geuenich, Dieter |editor3=Steuer, Heiko |author=Wolfram, Herwig|publisher=Walter de Gruyter|year=2006|language=German|volume=33|chapter=Waffensohn|isbn=978-3-11-018388-7|pages=49\u201351}}\n\n[[Category:5th-century births]]\n[[Category:508 deaths]]\n[[Category:5th-century rulers in Europe]]\n[[Category:6th-century rulers in Europe]]\n[[Category:Norwegian petty kings]]\n[[Category:Germanic rulers]]\n[[Category:Germanic warriors]]\n[[Category:Heruli]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses|Rodulf (disambiguation)}}\n'''King Rodulf''' is described by both [[Procopius]] and [[Paul the Deacon]] as the king of the [[Heruli]] kingdom on the [[Middle Danube]], who died when they were defeated by the [[Lombards]], some time between 494 and 508. After this defeat, in 512, Procopius reported that some of the Heruli nobility migrated north to [[Thule]] (what he called [[Scandinavia]]), settling near the ''Dani'' ([[Danes]]).\n\nIt is uncertain whether this Rodulf is the same king described in the ''[[Getica]]'' of [[Jordanes]] as the king of the [[Ranii]] on the island of [[Scandza]] (what he called Scandinavia), who left his kingdom near the ''Dani'' ([[Danes]]), and came to Italy, where he was embraced by the [[Ostrogoths|Ostrogothic]] [[King of Italy]], [[Theodoric the Great]]. Notably, Jordanes also mentions that the Heruli had been living in this area also, until they were driven out by the Danes, but he does not connect this Rodulf to these Heruli.\n\nThe Scandza passage of Jordanes is subject to many different interpretations, and some historians have proposed that Jordanes made errors. For example, [[Theodor Mommsen]] believed Jordanes should have described the Scandinavian Rudolf as a Herul, and the historian [[Herwig Wolfram]] has described this Scandinavian Rudolf as a [[Gaut]].<ref name=\"Wolfram2004p19\">Wolfram (2004) p. 49</ref>\n\nDue to the similarity of the circumstances, it has been suggested that the various accounts describe one individual, although this remains uncertain. Apart from the name Rudolf, the association with the region of the Dani, their apparent allegiance to Theoderic is notable. In a passage mentioning the Heruli, Jordanes mentioned that Theoderic adopted their king (who is not named in that passage) as a \"son in arms\". It is thus possible that Theoderic helped established him as king of the Heruli.\n\nMore speculatively, another debated issue is whether Rodulf could be the background for certain aspects of later heroic poetry, possibly including the [[Norsemen|Norse]] [[saga]] character [[Hr\u00f3lfr Kraki]].\n\n==King in Scandza==\n[[File:Jordanes, Norway tribes.png|thumb|340px|Locations of the tribes described by Jordanes in Norway, contemporary with, and some possibly ruled by Rodulf.]]\nKing Rodulf (''Roduulf rex'')<ref name=\"Maenchen\"/> of the Ranii tribe appears in the ''[[Getica]]'' (''De origine actibusque Getarum''; \"The Origin and Deeds of the Goths\") of the Roman historian [[Jordanes]]. Building on the now lost ''Historia Gothorum'' (\"History of the Goths\") of [[Cassiodorus]], Jordanes wrote his account at the request of [[Theodoric the Great]], King of the [[Ostrogoths]] and [[King of Italy|ruler of Italy]].<ref>Helle (2003) p. 82</ref> In the ''Getica'', it is said that Rodulf spurned his own kingdom,<ref name=\"Maenchen\">Maenchen-Helfen (1973) p. 487</ref> namely that of the \"Ranii\" tribe from Ragnaricii - Ranrike/Ranerike in today's Western Sweden. He therefore fled, likely together with a band of warriors,<ref>Skre (2008) p. 288</ref> to seek the sanctuary and support of Theodoric in [[Ravenna]] around 500.<ref name=\"Wolfram2004p19\"/>\n\nIt is unclear whether he was king of the Ranii tribe alone, or if he ruled all, or any other<ref name=\"Skre257\">Skre (2008) p. 257</ref> of the tribes described in the same context (as being the neighbours to the [[Heruli]], who were driven from their homes), namely the \"Granii, Augandzi, Eunixi, Taetel, Rugii, Aprochi.\"<ref name=\"Maenchen\"/> This list has been transliterated to mean the \"Grannii, A[u]gandzi, Eunixi <e>t Aetelrugi, Arothi,\"<ref>Nordgren (2004) p. 387</ref> and the tribes described identified as the inhabitants of [[Grenland]] (Grannii), [[Agder]] (A[u]gand''zi''), the \"island inhabitants\"<ref name=\"Nordgren\">Nordgren (2004) p. 464</ref> possibly of [[Karm\u00f8y]]<ref name=\"Thurston\">Thurston (1996) p. 111</ref> (Eunixi), the \"head [[Rugii]]\" of [[Rogaland]] (Aetelrugi) and [[Charudes|the inhabitants]] of [[Hordaland]] (Arothi).<ref name=\"Nordgren\"/> The vast geographic distances between the tribes, scattered throughout the Norwegian coast,<ref name=\"Skre257\"/> and the unlikeliness of a unified kingdom of such a magnitude at this early point<ref>Koht (1955) p. 12</ref> has been cited as arguments against such a possibility.\n\nSince the tribes are listed only in the context of being neighbours to the Heruli in the latter's former homeland, historian [[Otto J. Maenchen-Helfen]] thought it to be a linguistic error to interpret Rodulf as king of the tribes mentioned, instead holding that Rodulf should actually be read as king of the Heruli, as part of the greater context.<ref name=\"Maenchen\"/> Assuming that Rodulf had ruled all the tribes mentioned, historian Axel Kristinsson has speculated that it could have been natural for Rodulf to seek out some of his kinsmen, namely the southern Rugians who had joined the Ostrogoths as the Rogii sub-tribe after their kingdom was destroyed in 487.<ref>Kristinsson (2010) p. 225</ref> Historian A. H. Merrills, on the other hand, has proposed the possibility that placing Rodulf's origin with the Scandinavian tribes could have been politically motivated. Since Theodoric sought to expand his connections in the north at the time, his support of a northern exile would have given him significant benefits.<ref>Merrills (2005) p. 129</ref>\n\nSome modern historians have speculated that it could have been Rodulf, or potentially some of his subjects, who provided Cassiodorus or Jordanes with the information for their extensive lists and details of [[Scandinavia]]n peoples and tribes.<ref>Christensen (2002) pp. 270\u2013271, Fouracre (2005) p. 501, Skre (1998) p. 256, Goffart (2009) p. 64 and Merrills (2005) pp. 128\u2013129</ref> In any case, Rodulf was not the only Nordic warlord who visited the Goths and potentially could have provided knowledge about Scandinavian tribes.<ref>Skre (1998) pp. 256\u2013257</ref>\n\n==King of the Heruls==\nThe Byzantine scholar [[Procopius]] relates that the Heruli tribe had a king<ref name=\"ReallexikonKrag\"/> or leader (''h\u00e9gemon'')<ref>Weibull (1987) p. 8</ref> called Rodulf (''Rhodoulphos'') during the reign of the Byzantine emperor [[Anastasius I (emperor)|Anastasius]].<ref name=\"ReallexikonKrag\">Krag (2003) p. 58</ref> In the ''[[History of the Lombards|Historia Langobardorum]]'' (\"History of the Lombards\"), [[Paul the Deacon]] mentions that Rodulf was among the dead in a battle against the [[Lombards]]<ref name=\"ReallexikonKrag\"/> under [[Tato]], probably in 508.<ref name=\"ReallexikonWolfram\"/><ref name=\"Wolfram\"/> According to Procopius, Rodulf was enticed by his people to declare war against the Lombards, despite the latter's attempt of maintaining peace.<ref>Goffart (2009) pp. 207\u2013208</ref> A later version by Paul the Deacon gives Rodulf a legitimate ''[[casus belli]]'',<ref>Goffart (2009) p. 208</ref> as Rodulf purportedly declared war against the Lombards because his brother was murdered by Tato's daughter Rumetruda, after a fall-out between the two during his brother's return home after he had concluded peace with the Lombards.<ref name=\"Paul1XX\">Paul the Deacon, [http://www.northvegr.org/histories%20and%20chronicles/history%20of%20the%20lombards/005.html 1. XX]</ref> Theodoric did not manage to intervene in time, and the Heruls thus suffered a crushing defeat.<ref name=\"Wolfram\"/> The Heruls were split up as a result of the defeat in the battle.<ref name=\"ReallexikonKrag\"/> As Rodulf lost both his standard (''vexillum'') and his helmet, both considered irreplaceable in Germanic thought, he was the last true king of the Heruls.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Journal of Roman Studies|publisher=Kraus Reprint|year=1968|volume=40-42|page=204|url=https://books.google.com/books?ei=uinnUIDCG6bl4QS7woGYBQ&hl=no&id=zys8AAAAMAAJ&dq=rodulf+germanic+herul&q=%22because+in+Germanic+thought%22#search_anchor}}</ref>\n[[File:Theoderic Quarter Siliqua 80000847.jpg|thumb|210px|Coin of Theodoric the Great.]]\n\nJordanes also tells of an unnamed king of the Heruli, who has been identified with Rodulf by some historians.<ref name=\"ReallexikonKrag\"/> He writes that Theodoric adopted a king of the Heruli as his \"son in arms,\" by giving him a horse, sword and shield (possibly around 507)<ref name=\"ReallexikonWolfram\">Wolfram (2006) p. 50</ref> similarly to what his father [[Theodemir (Ostrogothic king)|Theodemir]] formerly had done with the [[Suebi]] chieftain [[Hunimund]].<ref name=\"Wolfram\"/> The accompanying letter to the king, which was translated into \"German,\" read that the king would \"hold the first rank among the peoples.\"<ref name=\"ReallexikonWolfram\"/><ref name=\"Wolfram\"/> In a letter referred to by Cassiodorus, probably from between 507 and 514, Theodoric asks for the assistance of the kings of the Heruli, [[Thuringii|Thuringi]] and [[Warini|Varni]] tribes for a counter-attack against the pressure from the [[Franks]].<ref name=\"ReallexikonKrag\"/> Although Procopius claims the battle took place in 494, the battle, which led to Rodulf's death, is therefore considered unlikely to have occurred before 508.<ref name=\"ReallexikonKrag\"/>\n\nThe Heruls are considered to have been an originally Scandinavian people.<ref name=\"ReallexikonKrag\"/> After migrating southwards, the group later settled at the river [[Morava (river)|Morava]] following the Ostrogothic departure from [[Pannonian Basin|Pannonia]] in 473, and established a federated kingdom that extended across the Danube and into the Roman Empire. After becoming ruler of Italy, Theodoric travelled to what was described as the previous homeland of the [[Goths]], and thereafter, according to historian [[Herwig Wolfram]], wanted to establish an alliance with the Heruli king Rodulf. According to Wolfram, Rodulf \"probably included in his sphere of influence the region north of [[Lake Balaton]].\"<ref name=\"Wolfram\">Wolfram (1990) p. 318</ref>\n\n==Identifying Rodulf==\nThe German [[Classics|classicist]] [[Theodor Mommsen]] argued that the Rodulf of the Ranii tribe and the Rodulf of the Heruli tribe constituted the same person. He proposed that Rodulf could have arrived to Theodoric in 489, when he was in [[Moesia]].<ref name=\"Skre257\"/> Similarly, the scientist-explorer [[Fridtjof Nansen]] proposed that \"Heruli\" at first perhaps was a common name for bands of northern warriors, who to a certain degree consisted of Norwegians. In his book ''In northern mists'', Nansen suggested that Rodulf of the Ranii tribe could have migrated south with a band of warriors, and that on arriving at the [[Danube]], pressed by other warlike tribes in the vicinity, he sought alliance with Theodoric. Nansen believed this could have happened before Theodoric's invasion of [[Italy]] in 489, at the same time that the Heruli were just north of the Danube, and were the nearest neighbours of the Goths.<ref name=\"Nansen\">Nansen (1911) pp. 137\u2013139</ref>\n\nAlthough particularly German scholarship have identified the unnamed Heruli king and the Rodulfs as the same person,<ref name=\"Goffart3356\">Goffart (2009) pp. 335\u2013336</ref> including the ''[[Reallexikon der Germanischen Altertumskunde]]'' in an entry by Norwegian historian [[Claus Krag]],<ref name=\"ReallexikonKrag\"/> others such as historian [[Walter Goffart]] and archaeologist Dagfinn Skre have questioned at least parts of these identifications.<ref>Skre (1998) p. 257 and Goffart (2009) pp. 335\u2013336</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nIn the early 6th century, the Lombard king [[Wacho]] took [[Silinga of the Heruli|Silinga]] as his third wife, who was said to be the daughter of the last king of the Heruls.<ref>Waldman and Mason (2006) p. 389</ref> This has led some scholars to believe that Silinga probably was a daughter of Rodulf;<ref>{{Cite book|title=[[Reallexikon der Germanischen Altertumskunde]]|editor1=Beck, Heinrich |editor2=Geuenich, Dieter |editor3=Steuer, Heiko |publisher=Walter de Gruyter|year=2006|language=German|volume=33|isbn=978-3-11-018388-7|page=6}}</ref> she again had the son [[Walthari]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Zeitschrift f\u00fcr die Geschichte des Oberrheins|url=https://books.google.com/books?ei=mjbnUMLPDoiN4ATvo4C4Cw&hl=no&id=pxtoAAAAMAAJ&dq=%22silinga%22+rodulf&q=%22sohnes+walthari%22#search_anchor|volume=149|publisher=G. Braun.|year=2001|page=36|language=German}}</ref> The marriage between Wacho and Silinga functioned to legitimize the Lombards as the successors to the kingdom of the Heruls.<ref>Wolfram (1995) p. 21</ref>\n\nIt has been debated whether Rodulf may have influenced later heroic poetry, since the causes of the war between the Lombards and the Heruli (as reported by Paul the Deacon) concerns related issues. Some have furthermore argued that Rodulf could be the background for the character [[Hr\u00f3lfr Kraki]] who appears in the later [[saga]]s. Evidence for this includes the significant similarities between the traditions of, on the one side, the [[Scylding]]s of the ''[[Skj\u00f6ldunga saga]]'' and the [[Yngling|Scylfings]] of the Swedish sagas, and on the other, historical knowledge of the environment around the Heruli, Goths and [[Hun]]s.<ref>Krag (2003) pp. 58\u201359</ref>\n\nIt has also been speculated that the R\u00e1\u00f0ulfr mentioned in the [[R\u00f6k Runestone]] (which also mentions Theodoric the Great) could be identical with Rodulf.<ref name=\"Nansen\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n===Primary sources===\n* [[Cassiodorus]], ''The Letters of Cassiodorus'', [http://www.gutenberg.org/files/18590/18590-h/18590-h.htm#Page_236 IV. 2.], [http://www.gutenberg.org/files/18590/18590-h/18590-h.htm#Page_198 III. 3.]\n* [[Jordanes]], ''The Origin and Deeds of the Goths'', [http://www.romansonline.com/Src_Frame.asp?DocID=Gth_Goth_03 3. 24.]\n* [[Paul the Deacon]], ''History of the Lombards'', [http://www.northvegr.org/histories%20and%20chronicles/history%20of%20the%20lombards/005.html I. XX.]\n* [[Procopius]], ''The Wars of Justinian'', [http://www.gutenberg.org/files/20298/20298-h/20298-h.htm#VI_xiv_11 VI. xiv.]\n\n===Modern sources===\n* {{Cite book|title=The New Cambridge Medieval History: Volume 1, c.500-c.700|author=Fouracre, Paul|publisher=Cambridge University|year=2005|isbn=978-0-521-36291-7|page=501}}\n* {{Cite book|title=Barbarian Tides: The Migration Age and the Later Roman Empire|author=[[Walter Goffart|Goffart, Walter]]|publisher=University of Pennsylvania|year=2009|isbn=978-0-8122-2105-3}}\n* {{Cite book|title=The Cambridge History of Scandinavia|volume=1|author=[[Knut Helle|Helle, Knut]]|publisher=Cambridge University|year=2003|isbn=978-0-521-47299-9|page=82}}\n* {{Cite book|title= Harald H\u00e5rfagre og rikssamlinga |author=[[Halvdan Koht|Koht, Halvdan]]|publisher=Aschehoug|year=1955|language=Norwegian|page=12}}\n* {{Cite book|title=[[Reallexikon der Germanischen Altertumskunde]]|author=[[Claus Krag|Krag, Claus]]|publisher=Walter de Gruyter|volume=25|year=2003|language=German|chapter=Rodulf|editor=Beck, Heinrich |editor2=Geuenich, Dieter |editor3=Steuer, Heiko|isbn=3-11-017733-1|pages=58\u201359}}\n* {{Cite book|title=Expansions: Competition and Conquest in Europe since the Bronze Age|author=Kristinsson, Axel|publisher=Reykjav\u00edkurAkadem\u00edan|year=201