hor=[[Herwig Wolfram|Wolfram, Herwig]]|publisher=University of California|year=1990|origyear=First published in Germany in 1979|language=German|isbn=0-520-06983-8|page=318}}\n* {{Cite book|title=Salzburg, Bayern, \u00d6sterreich: Conversio Bagoariorum et Carantanorum und die Quellen ihrer Zeit|author=Wolfram, Herwig|publisher=Oldenbourg Verlag|year=1995|language=German|isbn=978-3-7029-0404-3}}\n* {{Cite book|title=Early Germanic Literature and Culture|editor=Murdoch, Brian |editor2=Read, Malcolm Kevin|author=Wolfram, Herwig|publisher=Boydell & Brewer|year=2004|chapter=Origo Gentis: The Literature of Germanic Origins|isbn=1-57113-199-X|pages=39\u201354}}\n* {{Cite book|title=[[Reallexikon der Germanischen Altertumskunde]]|editor1=Beck, Heinrich |editor2=Geuenich, Dieter |editor3=Steuer, Heiko |author=Wolfram, Herwig|publisher=Walter de Gruyter|year=2006|language=German|volume=33|chapter=Waffensohn|isbn=978-3-11-018388-7|pages=49\u201351}}\n\n[[Category:5th-century births]]\n[[Category:508 deaths]]\n[[Category:5th-century rulers in Europe]]\n[[Category:6th-century rulers in Europe]]\n[[Category:Norwegian petty kings]]\n[[Category:Germanic rulers]]\n[[Category:Germanic warriors]]\n[[Category:Heruli]]\n", "name_user": "Andrew Lancaster", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rodulf_(petty_king)"}
{"title_page": "A Drunkard's Reformation", "text_new": "{{short description|1909 film}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = A Drunkard's Reformation\n| image          = Opening_credits_from_silent_film_A_Drunkard's_Reformation_(1909).jpg\n| caption        = Opening credits from film \n| director       = [[D. W. Griffith]]\n| producer       = \n| writer         = D. W. Griffith\n| starring       = [[Arthur V. Johnson]]\n| cinematography = [[G. W. Bitzer]]\n| editing        = \n| studio         = \n| distributor    = [[Biograph Company]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1909|4|1}}\n| runtime        = 13 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = Silent with English intertitles\n}}\n\n'''''A Drunkard's Reformation''''' is a 1909 American [[drama film]] directed by [[D. W. Griffith]]. Prints of the film survive in the film archive of the [[Library of Congress]].<ref name=\"silentera\">{{cite web |url=http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/D/DrunkardsReformation1909.html |title=Progressive Silent Film List: A Drunkard's Reformation |accessdate=October 6, 2008|work=Silent Era}}</ref> Biograph advertised the feature as \"The most powerful [[Temperance movement|temperance lecture]] ever depicted\".<ref>{{cite magazine | url=https://archive.org/stream/moviwor04chal#page/n371/mode/2up | title=Biograph Films | magazine=The Moving Picture World | date=1909 | author=Biograph Films | pages=357}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nJohn Wharton, the husband of a true and trusting wife and father of an eight-year-old girl, through the association of rakish companions becomes addicted to the drink habit, and while the demon rum has not fastened its tentacles firmly, there is no question that given free rein the inevitable would culminate in time. Arriving home one afternoon in a wine besotted condition, he is indeed a terrifying spectacle to his little family. Later, after he has slept off the effects to some extent, while at supper, the little girl shows him two tickets for the theater, begging him to take her. After some persuasion he consents to go. The play is a dramatization of [[\u00c9mile Zola|\u00c9mile Zola's]] ''[[L'Assommoir]]'', which shows how short a journey it is from peace and happiness to woe and despair by the road of rum. At the final curtain of the play, he is a changed man, going homeward with a firm determination that he will drink no more, which he promises his wife upon his return. Two years later we find the little family seated, happy and peaceful, at the fireside and we know that the promise has been kept.\n::''Moving Picture World'' (1909)\n\n==Cast==\n[[File:Silent film A Drunkard's Reformation (1909).ogv|thumb|right|A Drunkard's Reformation]]\n* [[Arthur V. Johnson]] - John Wharton\n* [[Linda Arvidson]] - Mrs. John Wharton\n* [[Adele DeGarde]] - The Wharton Daughter\n* [[Charles Avery]] - In the Play\n* [[John R. Cumpson]] - In the Orchestra / In the Bar\n* [[Robert Harron]] - Theatre Usher\n* [[Anita Hendrie]] - In the Play / In the Audience\n* [[Florence Lawrence]] - In the Play\n* [[Marion Leonard]] - In the Play\n* [[David Miles (actor)]] - In the Play\n* [[Owen Moore]] - In the Play\n* [[Thomas J. Moore|Tom Moore]] - In the Audience\n* [[Herbert Prior]] - In the Bar\n* [[Mack Sennett]] - In the Play / In the Orchestra / In the Bar\n* [[Harry Solter]] - In the Play\n* [[Herbert Yost]] - In the Play\n\n==Background==\nA [[Movie theater|moving picture house]] manager in [[Moline, Illinois]], George Dehl, promised to donate $500 to a local hospital if he could not produce films that have the best sermons beat. Dehl proposed \"that they bring the Reverend [[Billy Sunday]] to Moline and have him preach the best sermon in the list, and they bring a great temperance lecturer here and instruct him to make his best effort\". Dehl said once they had left, he would put on two reels of film at his theater, and if the public does not vote one of them a greater temperance sermon than what the speaker had delivered, and the other a greater religious appeal than the sermon by Sunday, he would donate the money to a local hospital. The films he had referred for showing were ''The Drunkard's Reformation'' and ''The Resurrection''.<ref>{{cite magazine | url=https://archive.org/stream/moviwor10chal#page/n411/mode/2up | title=Pittsburg | magazine=Moving Picture World | date=1909 | pages=406}}</ref>\n\n''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' reported that Biograph had received a letter from an exhibitor in an [[Iowa]] town, stating that when the film was shown there, it had caused the town to [[Dry county|\"go dry\"]] at the election which occurred the week after it had been featured. The letter went on to say that the exhibitor had been visited by a delegation of \"The Wets\", asking for the picture not to be shown. The man refused and the town \"went [[prohibition]] by a big majority\".<ref>{{cite magazine | url=https://archive.org/stream/variety15-1909-06#page/n47/mode/2up | title=The Value of Quality | magazine=Variety | date=June 1909 | pages=13}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of American films of 1909]]\n* [[D. W. Griffith filmography]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0000852|title=A Drunkard's Reformation}}\n*{{AFI film|id=35840|title=A Drunkard's Reformation}}\n*{{Tcmdb title|id=509445|title=A Drunkard's Reformation}}\n{{D. W. Griffith}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Drunkards Reformation, A}}\n[[Category:1909 films]]\n[[Category:1909 drama films]]\n[[Category:1909 short films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American drama films]]\n[[Category:American silent short films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Biograph Company films]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Films directed by D. W. Griffith]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1909 film}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = A Drunkard's Reformation\n| image          = Opening_credits_from_silent_film_A_Drunkard's_Reformation_(1909).jpg\n| caption        = Opening credits from film \n| director       = [[D. W. Griffith]]\n| producer       = \n| writer         = D. W. Griffith\n| starring       = [[Arthur V. Johnson]]\n| cinematography = [[G. W. Bitzer]]\n| editing        = \n| studio         = \n| distributor    = [[Biograph Company]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1909|4|1}}\n| runtime        = 13 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = Silent with English intertitles\n}}\n\n'''''A Drunkard's Reformation''''' is a 1909 American [[drama film]] directed by [[D. W. Griffith]]. Prints of the film survive in the film archive of the [[Library of Congress]].<ref name=\"silentera\">{{cite web |url=http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/D/DrunkardsReformation1909.html |title=Progressive Silent Film List: A Drunkard's Reformation |accessdate=October 6, 2008|work=Silent Era}}</ref> Biograph advertised the feature as \"The most powerful [[Temperance movement|temperance lecture]] ever depicted\".<ref>{{cite magazine | url=https://archive.org/stream/moviwor04chal#page/n371/mode/2up | title=Biograph Films | magazine=The Moving Picture World | date=1909 | author=Biograph Films | pages=357}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nJohn Wharton, the husband of a true and trusting wife and father of an eight-year-old girl, through the association of rakish companions becomes addicted to the drink habit, and while the demon rum has not fastened its tentacles firmly, there is no question that given free rein the inevitable would culminate in time. Arriving home one afternoon in a wine besotted condition, he is indeed a terrifying spectacle to his little family. Later, after he has slept off the effects to some extent, while at supper, the little girl shows him two tickets for the theater, begging him to take her. After some persuasion he consents to go. The play is a dramatization of [[\u00c9mile Zola|\u00c9mile Zola's]] ''[[L'Assommoir]]'', which shows how short a journey it is from peace and happiness to woe and despair by the road of rum. At the final curtain of the play, he is a changed man, going homeward with a firm determination that he will drink no more, which he promises his wife upon his return. Two years later we find the little family seated, happy and peaceful, at the fireside and we know that the promise has been kept.\n::''Moving Picture World'' (1909)\n\n==Cast==\n[[File:Silent film A Drunkard's Reformation (1909).ogv|thumb|right|A Drunkard's Reformation]]\n* [[Arthur V. Johnson]] - John Wharton\n* [[Linda Arvidson]] - Mrs. John Wharton\n* [[Adele DeGarde]] - The Wharton Daughter\n* [[Charles Avery]] - In the Play\n* [[John R. Cumpson]] - In the Orchestra / In the Bar\n* [[Robert Harron]] - Theatre Usher\n* [[Anita Hendrie]] - In the Play / In the Audience\n* [[Florence Lawrence]] - In the Play\n* [[Marion Leonard]] - In the Play\n* [[David Miles (actor)]] - In the Play\n* [[Owen Moore]] - In the Play\n* [[Thomas J. Moore|Tom Moore]] - In the Audience\n* [[Herbert Prior]] - In the Bar\n* [[Mack Sennett]] - In the Play / In the Orchestra / In the Bar\n* [[Harry Solter]] - In the Play\n* [[Herbert Yost]] - In the Play\n\n==Background==\nA [[Movie theater|moving picture house]] manager in [[Moline, Illinois]], George Dehl, promised to donate $500 to a local hospital if he could not produce films that have the best sermons beat. Dehl proposed \"that they bring the Reverend [[Billy Sunday]] to Moline and have him preach the best sermon in the list, and they bring a great temperance lecturer here and instruct him to make his best effort\". Dehl said once they had left, he would put on two reels of film at his theater, and if the public does not vote one of them a greater temperance sermon than what the speaker had delivered, and the other a greater religious appeal than the sermon by Sunday, he would donate the money to a local hospital. The films he had referred for showing were ''The Drunkard's Reformation'' and ''The Resurrection''.<ref>{{cite magazine | url=https://archive.org/stream/moviwor10chal#page/n411/mode/2up | title=Pittsburg | magazine=Moving Picture World | date=1909 | pages=406}}</ref>\n\n''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' reported that Biograph had received a letter from an exhibitor in an [[Iowa]] town, stating that when the film was shown there, it had caused the town to [[Dry county|\"go dry\"]] at the election which occurred the week after it had been featured. The letter went on to say that the exhibitor had been visited by a delegation of \"The Wets\", asking for the picture not to be shown. The man refused and the town \"went [[prohibition]] by a big majority\".<ref>{{cite magazine | url=https://archive.org/stream/variety15-1909-06#page/n47/mode/2up | title=The Value of Quality | magazine=Variety | date=June 1909 | pages=13}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of American films of 1909]]\n* [[D. W. Griffith filmography]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0000852|title=A Drunkard's Reformation}}\n*{{AFI film|id=35840|title=A Drunkard's Reformation}}\n*{{Tcmdb title|id=509445|title=A Drunkard's Reformation}}\n{{D. W. Griffith}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Drunkards Reformation, A}}\n[[Category:1909 films]]\n[[Category:1909 drama films]]\n[[Category:1909 short films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American drama films]]\n[[Category:American silent short films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Biograph Company films]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Films directed by D. W. Griffith]]\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A_Drunkard%27s_Reformation"}
{"title_page": "Siberian Coal Energy Company", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name             = Siberian Coal Energy Company<br/>SUEK\n| logo             =SUEK Logo.svg \n| caption          = \n| type             = [[Private limited company|Private]] (Joint stock company)\n| fate             = \n| predecessor      = \n| successor        = \n| foundation       = {{Start date|2001}}\n| founder          = [[Andrey Melnichenko (industrialist)|Andrey Melnichenko]] \n| defunct          = \n| location_city    = [[Moscow]]\n| location_country = Russia\n| location         = \n| locations        = \n| area_served      = Siberia and Far East\n| key_people       = Andrey Melnichenko (chairman)<br/>[[Vladimir Rashevsky]] (CEO)<br/>[[Alexander Landia]] (Senior independent director)\n| industry         = Coal mining and energy producing\n| products         = Coal and energy\n| services         = \n| revenue           = {{wikidata revenue|revenue|num}}{{wikidata revenue|revenue|ref}}\n| revenue_year      = {{wikidata revenue|revenue|year}}\n| operating_income  = {{wikidata revenue|operating_income|num}}{{wikidata revenue|operating_income|ref}}\n| income_year       = {{wikidata revenue|operating_income|year}}\n| net_income        = {{wikidata revenue|net_income|num}}{{wikidata revenue|net_income|ref}}\n| net_income_year   = {{wikidata revenue|net_income|year}}\n| assets            = {{wikidata revenue|assets|num}}{{wikidata revenue|assets|ref}}\n| assets_year       = {{wikidata revenue|assets|year}}\n| equity            = {{wikidata revenue|equity|num}}{{wikidata revenue|equity|ref}}\n| equity_year       = {{wikidata revenue|equity|year}}\n| owner            = [[Andrey Melnichenko (industrialist)|Andrey Melnichenko]] (92.2%)\n| num_employees    = 70,000 (2020)\n| parent           = SUEK Plc\n| divisions        = \n| subsid           = \n| homepage         = {{url|www.suek.com}}\n| footnotes        = \n| intl             = \n}}\n\n'''Siberian Coal Energy Company''' (SUEK) is one of top-ten global coal producers by output, international sales and reserves, and Russia's largest coal producer. It has affiliates and subsidiaries in [[Kemerovo region]], [[Altai region]], [[Krasnoyarsk region]], [[Novosibirsk region]], [[Khakassia]], [[Tyva]], [[Zabaikalye region]], [[Buryatia|Buryatia]], [[Primorye region]], [[Khabarovsk region]], and [[Murmansk region]].\n\n==History==\nIn February 2007, SUEK and [[Gazprom]] agreed to establish a joint company on the basis of their electricity and coal assets. The shares of new company would have been divided on the basis of 50% plus 1 share to Gazprom and 50% minus 1 share to SUEK. However, that deal was abandoned.<ref name=kommersant100608>\n{{cite news\n | url= http://www.kommersant.com/p901939/r_500/Gazprom_SUEK_abandon_/\n | title = Gazprom, SUEK Drifted Apart\n | newspaper = [[Kommersant]]\n | date=2008-06-10\n | accessdate=2011-01-01}}\n</ref>\n\nIn June 2010, SUEK obtained regulatory approval to list up to 25% of its shares abroad. However, in August 2010 the [[Initial public offering|IPO]] was postponed for an unspecified period.<ref name=reuters020810>\n{{cite news\n | url= http://uk.reuters.com/article/idUKLDE66F0AP20100802\n | title = Russian miner SUEK not planning IPO for a year-IFX\n | first = Nastassia | last = Astrasheuskaya\n | agency = [[Reuters]]\n | date=2010-08-02\n | accessdate=2011-01-01}}\n</ref><ref name=\"reuters080611\">{{cite news\n | url= http://uk.reuters.com/article/2011/06/08/russia-coal-ipo-idAFLDE7571DB20110608\n | title = Russia's SUEK puts IPO on hold as ownership changes\n | first = Polina | last = Devitt\n | agency = [[Reuters]]\n | date=2011-06-08\n | accessdate=2012-03-05}}\n</ref>\n\nIn February 2012, SUEK bought 24.9% stake in the Murmansk port.<ref name=reuters220212>\n{{cite news\n | url= http://uk.reuters.com/article/2012/02/22/russia-suek-murmansk-idUSL5E8DMA2L20120222\n | title = SUEK buys 24.9 pct of Murmansk port\n | first = Jacqueline | last = Cowhig\n | agency = [[Reuters]]\n | date=2012-02-22\n | accessdate=2012-03-05}}\n</ref>\n\nIn August 2018, SUEK consolidated the Siberian Generating Company (SGC).\n\nAt the end 2019, SUEK acquired Reftinskaya GRES located in the Sverdlovsk region and agreed on the purchase of the Krasnoyarskaya GRES-2. This will\nmakes SUEK No. 5 electricity producer in Russia.\n\n==Operations==\nSUEK provides about 38% of coal in the Russian market and about 25% of Russian coal exports.<ref name=AR2014>\n{{cite news\n | url= http://www.suek.com/en/investors/reporting/#fs_15\n | title = SUEK 2014 Annual Report\n | work= www.suek.com\n | date=2015-05-01\n | accessdate=2016-03-18}}\n</ref>  It develops Kharanor, East, and Tugnuisky deposits of coal, and has a license for the development of the Nicholas deposit.  In 2015, SUEK produced 97.8&nbsp;million tons of coal.<ref name=suek11032016>\n{{cite news\n |url         = http://www.suek.com/en/media/news/2015FYIFRS/\n |title       = SUEK Group announces IFRS 2015 results\n |work        = suek.com\n |date        = 2016-03-11\n |accessdate  = 2016-03-18\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20160913192814/http://www.suek.com/en/media/news/2015FYIFRS/\n |archivedate = 2016-09-13\n}}\n</ref>\n\nIn addition to the coal mines, SUEK was a shareholder in several Siberian and Far-Eastern power companies, most prominently in [[Kuzbassenergo]] (TGK-12) and [[Yenisei TGK]] (TGK-13). However, in April 2011 the company announced a plan to de-merge its power assets.  As the first stage of de-merging, the power assets were transferred to Siberian Energy Investments Ltd., a holding company controlled by the SUEK's major shareholder Donalink Ltd.<ref name=suek150411>\n{{cite press release\n |url         = http://www.suek.ru/en/page.php?id=306&article=4139\n |title       = OJSC SUEK announces intention to demerge its power generation business\n |publisher   = SUEK\n |date        = 2011-04-15\n |accessdate  = 2012-03-05\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20120221073253/http://www.suek.ru/en/page.php?id=306\n |archivedate = 2012-02-21\n}}\n</ref><ref name=reuters250411a>\n{{cite news\n |url        = https://www.reuters.com/finance/stocks/KZBGY.PK/key-developments/article/2304118\n |archive-url = https://archive.is/20130201053146/http://www.reuters.com/finance/stocks/KZBGY.PK/key-developments/article/2304118\n |url-status   = dead\n |archive-date = 2013-02-01\n |title      = SUEK OAO Sells Its 50% Stake In Kuzbassenergo OAO-SKRIN\n |agency     = [[Reuters]]\n |date       = 2011-04-25\n |accessdate = 2012-03-05\n}}\n</ref><ref name=reuters250411b>\n{{cite news\n |url        = https://www.reuters.com/finance/stocks/KZBGY.PK/key-developments/article/2304120\n |archive-url = https://archive.is/20130201060919/http://www.reuters.com/finance/stocks/KZBGY.PK/key-developments/article/2304120\n |url-status   = dead\n |archive-date = 2013-02-01\n |title      = SIBERIAN ENERGY INVESTMENTS LTD Increases Its Stake In Kuzbassenergo OAO-SKRIN\n |agency     = [[Reuters]]\n |date       = 2011-04-25\n |accessdate = 2012-03-05\n}}\n</ref>\n\n==Owners==\nThe chairman of the board of directors is [[Andrey Melnichenko (industrialist)|Andrey Melnichenko]] and the CEO is [[Vladimir Rashevsky]], a minor shareholder of the company.  One hundred percent of SUEK shares are owned by SUEK Plc, a Cyprus-registered company controlled by Andrey Melnichenko.<ref name=\"reuters080611\"/>\n\n== See also ==\n* {{Portal-inline|Russia}}\n* {{Portal-inline|Energy}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://www.suek.com/en/}}\n\n[[Category:Coal companies of Russia]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Moscow]]\n[[Category:Energy companies established in 2001]]\n[[Category:Non-renewable resource companies established in 2001]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| name             = Siberian Coal Energy Company<br/>SUEK\n| logo             =SUEK Logo.svg \n| caption          = \n| type             = [[Private limited company|Private]] (Joint stock company)\n| fate             = \n| predecessor      = \n| successor        = \n| foundation       = {{Start date|2001}}\n| founder          = [[Andrey Melnichenko (industrialist)|Andrey Melnichenko]] \n| defunct          = \n| location_city    = [[Moscow]]\n| location_country = Russia\n| location         = \n| locations        = \n| area_served      = Siberia and Far East\n| key_people       = Andrey Melnichenko (chairman)<br/>[[Vladimir Rashevsky]] (CEO)<br/>[[Alexander Landia]] (Senior independent director)\n| industry         = Coal mining and energy producing\n| products         = Coal and energy\n| services         = \n| revenue           = {{wikidata revenue|revenue|num}}{{wikidata revenue|revenue|ref}}\n| revenue_year      = {{wikidata revenue|revenue|year}}\n| operating_income  = {{wikidata revenue|operating_income|num}}{{wikidata revenue|operating_income|ref}}\n| income_year       = {{wikidata revenue|operating_income|year}}\n| net_income        = {{wikidata revenue|net_income|num}}{{wikidata revenue|net_income|ref}}\n| net_income_year   = {{wikidata revenue|net_income|year}}\n| assets            = {{wikidata revenue|assets|num}}{{wikidata revenue|assets|ref}}\n| assets_year       = {{wikidata revenue|assets|year}}\n| equity            = {{wikidata revenue|equity|num}}{{wikidata revenue|equity|ref}}\n| equity_year       = {{wikidata revenue|equity|year}}\n| owner            = [[Andrey Melnichenko (industrialist)|Andrey Melnichenko]] (92.2%)\n| num_employees    = 70,000 (2020)\n| parent           = SUEK Plc\n| divisions        = \n| subsid           = \n| homepage         = {{url|www.suek.com}}\n| footnotes        = \n| intl             = \n}}\n\n'''Siberian Coal Energy Company''' (SUEK) is one of top-ten global coal producers by output, international sales and reserves, and Russia's largest coal producer. It has affiliates and subsidiaries in [[Kemerovo region]], [[Altai region]], [[Krasnoyarsk region]], [[Novosibirsk region]], [[Khakassia]], [[Tyva]], [[Zabaikalye region]], [[Buryatia|Buryatia]], [[Primorye region]], [[Khabarovsk region]], and [[Murmansk region]].\n\n==History==\nIn February 2007, SUEK and [[Gazprom]] agreed to establish a joint company on the basis of their electricity and coal assets. The shares of new company would have been divided on the basis of 50% plus 1 share to Gazprom and 50% minus 1 share to SUEK. However, that deal was abandoned.<ref name=kommersant100608>\n{{cite news\n | url= http://www.kommersant.com/p901939/r_500/Gazprom_SUEK_abandon_/\n | title = Gazprom, SUEK Drifted Apart\n | newspaper = [[Kommersant]]\n | date=2008-06-10\n | accessdate=2011-01-01}}\n</ref>\n\nIn June 2010, SUEK obtained regulatory approval to list up to 25% of its shares abroad. However, in August 2010 the [[Initial public offering|IPO]] was postponed for an unspecified period.<ref name=reuters020810>\n{{cite news\n | url= http://uk.reuters.com/article/idUKLDE66F0AP20100802\n | title = Russian miner SUEK not planning IPO for a year-IFX\n | first = Nastassia | last = Astrasheuskaya\n | agency = [[Reuters]]\n | date=2010-08-02\n | accessdate=2011-01-01}}\n</ref><ref name=\"reuters080611\">{{cite news\n | url= http://uk.reuters.com/article/2011/06/08/russia-coal-ipo-idAFLDE7571DB20110608\n | title = Russia's SUEK puts IPO on hold as ownership changes\n | first = Polina | last = Devitt\n | agency = [[Reuters]]\n | date=2011-06-08\n | accessdate=2012-03-05}}\n</ref>\n\nIn December 2010, the [[Federal Antimonopoly Service]] determined collusion by SUEK and two other coal producers. These accusations were denied by SUEK.<ref name=bloomberg281210>\n{{cite news\n | url= https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-28/suek-says-not-involved-in-165-000-collusion-found-by-watchdog.html\n | title = Suek Says Not Involved in $165,000 Collusion Found by Watchdog\n | first = Ilya | last = Khrennikov\n | agency = [[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]]\n | date=2010-12-28\n | accessdate=2011-01-01}}\n</ref>\n\nIn February 2012, SUEK bought 24.9% stake in the Murmansk port.<ref name=reuters220212>\n{{cite news\n | url= http://uk.reuters.com/article/2012/02/22/russia-suek-murmansk-idUSL5E8DMA2L20120222\n | title = SUEK buys 24.9 pct of Murmansk port\n | first = Jacqueline | last = Cowhig\n | agency = [[Reuters]]\n | date=2012-02-22\n | accessdate=2012-03-05}}\n</ref>\n\nMoody's Investors Service has assigned a Ba3 corporate family rating (CFR) and a Ba3-PD probability of default rating to SUEK in October 2013. The assignment of ratings to SUEK follows the company's corporate reorganisation, as a result of which hard coal assets and logistics assets (Vanino Sea Bulk Terminal and Murmansk trade sea ports) will continue to be directly controlled by SUEK OJSC (100% subsidiary of SUEK) while brown coal deposits will be spun off and will be controlled directly by SUEK.<ref>https://www.moodys.com/research/Moodys-assigns-a-Ba3-first-time-rating-to-SUEK-PLC--PR_285554?WT.mc_id=NLTITLE_YYYYMMDD_PR_285554%3C%2fp%3E</ref>\n\n==Operations==\nSUEK provides about 38% of coal in the Russian market and about 25% of Russian coal exports.<ref name=AR2014>\n{{cite news\n | url= http://www.suek.com/en/investors/reporting/#fs_15\n | title = SUEK 2014 Annual Report\n | work= www.suek.com\n | date=2015-05-01\n | accessdate=2016-03-18}}\n</ref>  It develops Kharanor, East, and Tugnuisky deposits of coal, and has a license for the development of the Nicholas deposit.  In 2015, SUEK produced 97.8&nbsp;million tons of coal.<ref name=suek11032016>\n{{cite news\n |url         = http://www.suek.com/en/media/news/2015FYIFRS/\n |title       = SUEK Group announces IFRS 2015 results\n |work        = suek.com\n |date        = 2016-03-11\n |accessdate  = 2016-03-18\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20160913192814/http://www.suek.com/en/media/news/2015FYIFRS/\n |archivedate = 2016-09-13\n}}\n</ref>\n\nIn addition to the coal mines, SUEK was a shareholder in several Siberian and Far-Eastern power companies, most prominently in [[Kuzbassenergo]] (TGK-12) and [[Yenisei TGK]] (TGK-13). However, in April 2011 the company announced a plan to de-merge its power assets.  As the first stage of de-merging, the power assets were transferred to Siberian Energy Investments Ltd., a holding company controlled by the SUEK's major shareholder Donalink Ltd.<ref name=suek150411>\n{{cite press release\n |url         = http://www.suek.ru/en/page.php?id=306&article=4139\n |title       = OJSC SUEK announces intention to demerge its power generation business\n |publisher   = SUEK\n |date        = 2011-04-15\n |accessdate  = 2012-03-05\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20120221073253/http://www.suek.ru/en/page.php?id=306\n |archivedate = 2012-02-21\n}}\n</ref><ref name=reuters250411a>\n{{cite news\n |url        = https://www.reuters.com/finance/stocks/KZBGY.PK/key-developments/article/2304118\n |archive-url = https://archive.is/20130201053146/http://www.reuters.com/finance/stocks/KZBGY.PK/key-developments/article/2304118\n |url-status   = dead\n |archive-date = 2013-02-01\n |title      = SUEK OAO Sells Its 50% Stake In Kuzbassenergo OAO-SKRIN\n |agency     = [[Reuters]]\n |date       = 2011-04-25\n |accessdate = 2012-03-05\n}}\n</ref><ref name=reuters250411b>\n{{cite news\n |url        = https://www.reuters.com/finance/stocks/KZBGY.PK/key-developments/article/2304120\n |archive-url = https://archive.is/20130201060919/http://www.reuters.com/finance/stocks/KZBGY.PK/key-developments/article/2304120\n |url-status   = dead\n |archive-date = 2013-02-01\n |title      = SIBERIAN ENERGY INVESTMENTS LTD Increases Its Stake In Kuzbassenergo OAO-SKRIN\n |agency     = [[Reuters]]\n |date       = 2011-04-25\n |accessdate = 2012-03-05\n}}\n</ref>\n\n==Owners==\nThe chairman of the board of directors is [[Andrey Melnichenko (industrialist)|Andrey Melnichenko]] and the CEO is [[Vladimir Rashevsky]], a minor shareholder of the company.  One hundred percent of SUEK shares are owned by SUEK Plc, a Cyprus-registered company controlled by Andrey Melnichenko.<ref name=\"reuters080611\"/>\n\n== See also ==\n* {{Portal-inline|Russia}}\n* {{Portal-inline|Energy}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://www.suek.com/en/}}\n\n[[Category:Coal companies of Russia]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Moscow]]\n[[Category:Energy companies established in 2001]]\n[[Category:Non-renewable resource companies established in 2001]]\n", "name_user": "185.155.17.131", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eHistory)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Siberian_Coal_Energy_Company"}
